1 NOTE <b><u>Family History, the Lawrence Line.</u></b>
2 CONT
2 CONT The Lawrence line begins in Watford, for this particular story, when Wa
2 CONC lter Lawrence was born in March 1856 to Thomas and Myra, Walter was the S
2 CONC ixth child, of ten, with Four older brothers and a younger sister.
2 CONT
2 CONT In 1879 Walter, a painter and decorator, married Ellen Evans, still in W
2 CONC atford, and they started a family, with Mary being born in 1882 and Ger
2 CONC trude, a year later in 1883.
2 CONT In 1883 they emigrated to America, settling in Woodtick, Hartford, Conn
2 CONC ecticut, where in 1888 Walter Junior was borne.
2 CONT In 1910, according to the 1910 Census, Gertrude had been married, but w
2 CONC as living back with the family along with her son Kenneth who had been b
2 CONC orne the previous year.
2 CONT
2 CONT At some point between 1910 and 1916 Walter returns to England, back to W
2 CONC atford, the reason for his return is still unknown. Around 1916 Walter m
2 CONC eets Emily Archer, and they marry, again in Watford, and whilst his wif
2 CONC e and family live in America.
2 CONT Later in the 1920 Census, Ellen is shown as being a widow.
2 CONT In 1919 Evelyn is borne and in 1922 Margaret follows, all awhile Emily i
2 CONC s not aware of Walter's other family. In 1925, Emily is expecting Lesli
2 CONC e, but, at some point around April, somehow finds out about Walter's ot
2 CONC her family. This she did not take lightly, according to Evelyn's memory
2 CONC , Voices were raised, and things were thrown.
2 CONT Emily shopped Walter to the Police, and left to return to Windsor, wher
2 CONC e she moved in with her mother, initially.
2 CONT Evelyn, again recalls, being on a train, coming into Windsor Central st
2 CONC ation and looking out of the window, as they crossed the river, to see a h
2 CONC ost of Yellow Buttercups on Bath Island, which gives us the time line o
2 CONC f April/ May 1925.
2 CONT They lived in a number of properties in Windsor, first in Kepple Row, n
2 CONC ow under the new building of the Victoria Barracks, and then moving to N
2 CONC o. 4 Alma Cottages, Alma Road where Leslie was borne. (they moved to Al
2 CONC ma Cottages because it was cheaper).
2 CONT No. 4 Alma Cottages, no longer exists, but was where the entrance to th
2 CONC e carpark behind the Hope is.
2 CONT At some point between 1925 and 1930, Walter returned to America 3rd Feb
2 CONC ruary 1926 from Southampton, there is no evidence of Walter Senior serv
2 CONC ing time in prison here, where he returns to Ellen and Walter Junior, a
2 CONC nd can be found on the 1930 census.
