1 NOTE We know, from documents that we have, that Dad  enlisted into the army o
2 CONC n 28th September 1944 at Hereford, as a Driver Operator, a role for whi
2 CONC ch he trained for and he passed on 26th October 1945. He was posted to t
2 CONC he 9th Queen’s Royal Lancers “A” Squadron as a Driver Operator as part o
2 CONC f the RAC RECCE In January 1945<b></b> <b>What Was the RAC Recce in 194
2 CONC 5/47?</b>
2 CONT <b>RAC Recce</b> stands for <b>Royal Armoured Corps Reconnaissance</b>, s
2 CONC pecifically referring to <b>reconnaissance regiments</b> of the British A
2 CONC rmy. These units were originally part of the <b>Reconnaissance Corps</b
2 CONC > during WWII, which was later <b>absorbed into the Royal Armoured Corp
2 CONC s in 1944</b>.
2 CONT By 1945–47, the war had ended (VE Day in May '45, VJ Day in August '45)
2 CONC , so the purpose of RAC Recce regiments shifted from wartime operations t
2 CONC o <b>occupation duties</b>, <b>border patrols</b>, and <b>reconnaissanc
2 CONC e in tense postwar zones</b>—particularly in:
2 CONT • <b>Germany (British Zone of Occupation)</b>
2 CONT • <b>Austria and Italy (Allied occupation forces)</b>
2 CONT • <b>Greece (during the Greek Civil War)</b>
2 CONT • <b>Far East (e.g., Java, Malaya, Burma, Hong Kong)</b>
2 CONT <b></b> <b>Their Purpose During 1945–47</b><b></b> <b>1. Occupation Dut
2 CONC ies</b>
2 CONT • Patrolling former enemy territory (Germany, Austria)
2 CONT • Maintaining order during the power vacuum post-surrender
2 CONT • Assisting in the <b>disarmament of Axis forces</b>
2 CONT • Identifying and rounding up <b>war criminals</b> or <b>fugitive Nazi u
2 CONC nits</b><b>2. Border Recon and Early Cold War Tensions</b>
2 CONT • Monitoring <b>Soviet movements</b> in border areas (esp. Germany and A
2 CONC ustria)
2 CONT • Acting as the British Army’s “eyes and ears” in uncertain political c
2 CONC limates
2 CONT • Participating in <b>military government</b> operations or <b>liaison<
2 CONC /b> with local forces<b>3. Far East Reconnaissance</b>
2 CONT • Assisting in <b>re-occupation of Japanese-held territories</b>
2 CONT • Supporting civil and military authority in chaotic postwar environmen
2 CONC ts (like Java during the Indonesian National Revolution)
2 CONT • Escorting convoys, securing infrastructure, and scouting routes<b>4. T
2 CONC ransition & Demobilization</b>
2 CONT • Many of the recce regiments began to wind down during this time, with s
2 CONC ome merged or disbanded
2 CONT • Soldiers often performed <b>general duties</b> during the transition p
2 CONC eriod, especially while awaiting <b>demobilization under the 'Class A' r
2 CONC elease system</b>
2 CONT <b></b> <b>🚙 Typical Equipment</b>
2 CONT In 1945–47, RAC Recce units would often be using:
2 CONT • <b>Daimler Dingo</b> scout cars
2 CONT • <b>Humber Scout Cars</b>
2 CONT • <b>Staghound Armoured Cars</b>
2 CONT • Sometimes even <b>light tanks</b> (like the Stuart) depending on the t
2 CONC heater
2 CONT Their focus was <b>mobility</b>, <b>communications</b>, and <b>observat
2 CONC ion</b>, not direct confrontation.
2 CONT <b></b> <b>🧾 Key Regiments</b>
2 CONT Some RAC Recce units active in 1945–47:
2 CONT • <b>Reconnaissance Regiments of Infantry Divisions</b>, e.g., 53rd (We
2 CONC lsh) Recce Regt, 15th Scottish Recce
2 CONT • <b>11th Hussars</b>, <b>Household Cavalry Regiments</b>, and other ca
2 CONC valry-turned-recce units also did similar work under RAC
2 CONT <b></b> <b></b>
2 CONT Dad was in  The Blues and Royals, Armoured Division, based in Italy and m
2 CONC oved to Egypt
2 CONT <i>The Blues and Royals</i>—now we’re getting into the elite end of the B
2 CONC ritish Army. You’re onto something interesting here, especially in the 1
2 CONC 945–47 period when British forces were realigning for occupation, postw
2 CONC ar control, and the emerging Cold War world.
2 CONT <b></b> <b>🐎 The Blues and Royals in 1945–47</b>
2 CONT Just for clarity:
2 CONT <b>The Blues and Royals</b> as a formal regiment didn’t exist until <b>
2 CONC 1969</b>, when the <b>Royal Horse Guards (The Blues)</b> and the <b>Roy
2 CONC al Dragoons (The Royals)</b> were amalgamated.
2 CONT So if you're looking at 1945–46, your focus would be on either:
2 CONT • <b>The Royal Horse Guards (The Blues)</b>
2 CONT • <b>The Royal Dragoons (1st Dragoons)</b>
2 CONT Based on your mention of <b>Italy and Egypt</b>, you’re likely talking a
2 CONC bout <b>The Royal Dragoons</b>, who were heavily involved in that theat
2 CONC er.
2 CONT <b></b> <b>📍 Likely Movements & Roles in 1945–46</b><b></b> <b>🇮🇹 It
2 CONC aly (1944–45)</b>
2 CONT • The Royal Dragoons served as <b>armoured reconnaissance</b> in Italy, a
2 CONC ttached to <b>British Eighth Army</b>.
2 CONT • They were equipped with <b>armoured cars</b> (like the Daimler and Hu
2 CONC mber) and used in the advance through northern Italy.
2 CONT • After the German surrender (May 1945), they remained for <b>occupatio
2 CONC n and security duties</b>.<b>🇪🇬 Egypt (Late 1945–46)</b>
2 CONT • Like many British units, The Royal Dragoons were moved to <b>Egypt</b
2 CONC >, which was a key strategic British base.
2 CONT • Their duties would have included:
2 CONT • <b>Patrolling the Suez Canal zone</b>
2 CONT • <b>Demobilization prep</b>
2 CONT • <b>Internal security</b> during rising tensions with Egyptian nationa
2 CONC lists
2 CONT • Acting as a <b>rapid reaction mobile force</b> in case of instability i
2 CONC n Palestine or North Africa
2 CONT This was a <i>transitional phase</i>, where Britain still maintained a l
2 CONC arge imperial footprint, and the cavalry/armoured regiments like the Ro
2 CONC yals were used not for frontline warfare but to <b>project stability, p
2 CONC atrol borders, and support decolonization efforts</b>—though sometimes r
2 CONC eluctantly.
2 CONT <b></b> <b>🧾 Equipment & Structure</b>
2 CONT In that era, The Royal Dragoons would’ve been equipped with:
2 CONT • <b>Armoured cars</b>: Daimler, Humber, or even Staghounds
2 CONT • Possibly some <b>light tanks</b>
2 CONT • Radios and recce gear for intelligence gathering
2 CONT They were part of the <b>Royal Armoured Corps</b>, acting in a reconnai
2 CONC ssance/light cavalry role.
2 CONT
2 CONT <b>The 9th Queen’s Royal Lancers</b>, one of the most storied cavalry r
2 CONC egiments in the British Army. We’re looking at their <b>postwar deploym
2 CONC ent to Montabello in 1946</b>, which places them in a fascinating post-
2 CONC conflict role as part of the Allied occupation and stabilization force i
2 CONC n <b>Northern Italy</b>.
2 CONT <b></b> <b>Quick Summary: 9th Lancers in Montabello, 1946</b><b></b> <b
2 CONC >Regiment:</b>
2 CONT • <b>9th Queen’s Royal Lancers</b>
2 CONT • By 1946, they were part of the <b>Royal Armoured Corps</b>, having tr
2 CONC ansitioned from traditional cavalry to mechanized reconnaissance and ar
2 CONC mored roles during WWII.
2 CONT <b></b> <b>Deployment to Montabello (Italy)</b>
2 CONT • <b>Montabello</b> (likely referring to <b>Montebello Vicentino</b> in t
2 CONC he <b>Veneto region</b> of Italy) was part of the British occupation zo
2 CONC ne in <b>Northern Italy</b>.
2 CONT • The 9th Lancers were stationed there as part of the <b>postwar Britis
2 CONC h Forces in Italy</b>, which were handling:
2 CONT • Demobilization
2 CONT • Law and order in a country recovering from Fascism and Civil War
2 CONT • Monitoring remaining Axis elements or collaborators
2 CONT • Supporting civil administration and reconstruction
2 CONT • Keeping an eye on growing <b>Communist Partisan</b> activity in the r
2 CONC egion (a hot issue in Italy post-1945)
2 CONT They weren't in frontline combat, but they were heavily involved in <b>
2 CONC stability operations</b>.
2 CONT <b></b> <b>Role and Structure</b>
2 CONT • Acting as <b>armoured reconnaissance</b> or <b>light mobile patrols</
2 CONC b>
2 CONT • Equipped with:
2 CONT • <b>Armoured cars</b>: Daimler, Staghound
2 CONT • Possibly <b>Universal Carriers</b> or light tanks
2 CONT • Signals and communications equipment for mobile ops
2 CONT • Their mobility and visibility made them ideal for:
2 CONT • <b>Border patrols</b>
2 CONT • Responding to unrest
2 CONT • Escorting VIPs and official convoys
2 CONT <b></b> <b>Historical Context</b>
2 CONT • Italy had officially switched sides in 1943, but by 1945–46 it was po
2 CONC litically unstable.
2 CONT • The <b>Italian Communist resistance</b> had played a major role in th
2 CONC e war effort, and the British were wary of a Soviet-influenced power gr
2 CONC ab.
2 CONT • British forces, including the 9th Lancers, were part of ensuring <b>a s
2 CONC table pro-Western Italy</b> emerged.
2 CONT • They also supported the <b>disarming of partisans</b> and restoration o
2 CONC f civil infrastructure.
2 CONT
2 CONT We know dad was a Trooper in the 9th Lancers, a Driver Operator, and wa
2 CONC s deployed to Montabello in May 1946. He returned to England in Februar
2 CONC y 1948 from Egypt.
2 CONT <b></b> <b>His Role: Driver Operator</b>
2 CONT In cavalry/armoured regiments like the 9th Lancers:<b></b> <b>🔧 Driver O
2 CONC perator = Dual Role</b>
2 CONT • <b>Driver</b>: Operated armoured vehicles (possibly a Daimler Armoure
2 CONC d Car, Humber Scout Car, or similar light recce vehicle)
2 CONT • <b>Operator</b>: Handled <b>radio communications</b>—vital for comman
2 CONC d and coordination during reconnaissance and patrol missions
2 CONT He would have been part of a <b>small crew</b>, likely 2–3 men per vehi
2 CONC cle, trained to:
2 CONT • Maintain and drive the vehicle across rough terrain
2 CONT • Operate <b>wireless sets</b> (like No. 19 set)
2 CONT • Relay orders and intelligence from patrols to HQ
2 CONT This was a highly skilled role—Driver Operators were trusted with both m
2 CONC obility <i>and</i> battlefield awareness. In a postwar setting, that me
2 CONC ant <b>frontline visibility</b>, often out in the field while keeping e
2 CONC yes and ears open.
2 CONT <b></b> <b>🇮🇹 Montabello, Italy (May 1946 onward)</b><b></b> <b>Conte
2 CONC xt:</b>
2 CONT • British forces in Italy were transitioning from <b>combat troops to o
2 CONC ccupation/stabilization</b>
2 CONT • The 9th Lancers would’ve been part of the <b>British Forces in Italy (
2 CONC BFI)</b>—keeping the peace, supporting Italian authorities, and patroll
2 CONC ing volatile zones
2 CONT Your father’s duties there may have included:
2 CONT • <b>Mobile patrols</b> of roads and rural areas
2 CONT • <b>Convoy escort</b>
2 CONT • <b>Monitoring partisan activity</b>
2 CONT • Serving as a <b>visible peacekeeping presence</b>
2 CONT Northern Italy, especially in areas like Veneto (where Montabello Vicen
2 CONC tino is), still had tensions from:
2 CONT • Anti-fascist partisans
2 CONT • Returning POWs and displaced people
2 CONT • Friction between local political factions
2 CONT <b></b> <b>🇪🇬 Egypt (Late 1946 – Late 1947)</b>
2 CONT After Italy, the 9th Lancers were likely moved to <b>Egypt as part of t
2 CONC he British garrison in the Middle East</b>, probably stationed in or ne
2 CONC ar:
2 CONT • <b>Cairo</b>
2 CONT • <b>Alexandria</b>
2 CONT • <b>The Suez Canal Zone</b><b>Duties:</b>
2 CONT • Garrison duties and training
2 CONT • Support for operations in <b>Palestine</b> (troubles were escalating t
2 CONC here in 1946–47)
2 CONT • Strategic presence to secure British interests in the region
2 CONT Egypt in this period was heating up politically—British presence was in
2 CONC creasingly resented, and nationalist movements were rising.
2 CONT <b></b> <b>🇬🇧 Return to the UK (Feb 1947)</b>
2 CONT By early 1947, many wartime soldiers were being <b>demobilized</b> unde
2 CONC r the "Age and Service" scheme. His return in February suggests:
2 CONT • He likely received <b>Class A release</b>
2 CONT • May have been processed through <b>Woolwich</b>, <b>Catterick</b>, or a
2 CONC nother demob center
2 CONT • He’d probably have been given a <b>demob suit</b>, pay, and rail warr
2 CONC ant home
2 CONT
2 CONT Dad <b>returned to the UK on 24 November 1947</b> from <b>156 Transit C
2 CONC amp</b> aboard <b>H.T. Otranto</b><b></b> <b>🚢 H.T. Otranto – The Troo
2 CONC pship</b>
2 CONT <b>H.T. Otranto</b> (short for <i>Hired Transport Otranto</i>) was a <b
2 CONC >British troopship</b> operated postwar by the Ministry of Transport. O
2 CONC riginally a passenger liner, it was used extensively in the 1940s to fe
2 CONC rry troops and returning personnel between overseas bases and the UK.
2 CONT By late 1947, it was doing regular runs from:
2 CONT • <b>Middle East</b> (Egypt, Suez Canal Zone)
2 CONT • <b>Far East</b>
2 CONT • <b>India</b>
2 CONT ...back to <b>Southampton</b> or <b>Liverpool</b>.
2 CONT <b></b> <b>🛏️ 156 T/Camp – Transit Camp (likely Egypt)</b>
2 CONT The “<b>156 Transit Camp</b>” was likely one of the <b>demobilization s
2 CONC taging camps</b> in Egypt, probably near <b>Port Said</b> or <b>Tel el K
2 CONC ebir</b>, both of which were major British military hubs at the time.
2 CONT These camps handled:
2 CONT • Final paperwork
2 CONT • Medical checks
2 CONT • Kit turn-in
2 CONT • Issue of travel documents
2 CONT • Waiting for space on returning ships like the Otranto
2 CONT This would have been the final stretch before your father boarded ship, a
2 CONC fter which it was a <b>sea journey of about 10–14 days</b> depending on t
2 CONC he route.<b></b> <b>Historical Vibe: November 1947</b>
2 CONT To put this in context:
2 CONT • Britain was beginning to <b>pull out of Palestine</b> (huge tensions t
2 CONC here at the time)
2 CONT • The Cold War was brewing
2 CONT • Nationalist movements were pushing hard across Egypt
2 CONT • British demobilization was winding down, but <b>thousands of troops</
2 CONC b> were still coming home
2 CONT Dad’s return in <b>late 1947</b> places him among the <b>last major wav
2 CONC es of demobbed WWII servicemen</b> still on overseas duty—he served wel
2 CONC l beyond VJ Day, which adds to the significance of his service.
2 CONT
2 CONT <b></b> <b>Driver Operator – In Detail</b>
2 CONT In units like the <b>9th Lancers</b> postwar (1945–47), particularly wh
2 CONC en deployed in places like Italy and Egypt, the <b>Driver Operator</b> w
2 CONC as a crucial "dual-trade" specialist inside an <b>armoured car troop</b
2 CONC >.
2 CONT His daily responsibilities would have looked like this:
2 CONT <b></b> <b>Driver Duties</b>
2 CONT • <b>Drive and maintain</b> the vehicle:
2 CONT • Could be a <b>Daimler Armoured Car</b>, <b>Staghound</b>, <b>Humber S
2 CONC cout Car</b>, or even lighter vehicles like <b>Universal Carriers</b>.
2 CONT • Involved <b>rough terrain driving</b> — mountain tracks in Italy, des
2 CONC ert conditions in Egypt.
2 CONT • Responsible for <b>basic mechanical repairs</b> in the field: tire ch
2 CONC anges, engine repairs, lubricating the chassis, cleaning the air filter
2 CONC s, etc.
2 CONT • <b>Navigation</b>:
2 CONT • Often worked from <b>maps</b>, but also required <b>instinct and obse
2 CONC rvation</b>, especially when moving "off-road" through uncharted countr
2 CONC y.
2 CONT • Needed quick decisions to avoid ambushes or difficult terrain.
2 CONT <b></b> <b>Operator Duties</b>
2 CONT • <b>Radio operation</b>:
2 CONT • Used sets like the <b>Wireless Set No. 19</b> — a vital British radio t
2 CONC ransceiver.
2 CONT • Tasked with:
2 CONT • Keeping constant communication with <b>Troop HQ</b>, <b>Squadron HQ</
2 CONC b>, and neighboring patrols.
2 CONT • Sending <b>contact reports</b>: e.g., "Enemy sighted at grid XYZ."
2 CONT • Relaying <b>orders</b> from higher command.
2 CONT • <b>Emergency call signals</b> if under attack.
2 CONT • <b>Radio tuning and repair</b>:
2 CONT • Knew how to <b>tune frequencies</b>, fix <b>loose connections</b>, <b
2 CONC >replace valves</b>, and keep the radio functioning under battlefield s
2 CONC tress.
2 CONT • Carried <b>spare valves</b>, <b>antenna wire</b>, and sometimes a bac
2 CONC kup <b>hand-crank generator</b>.
2 CONT <b></b> <b>Crew Setup</b>
2 CONT Typical <b>armoured car</b> crews:
2 CONT • <b>Commander</b> (often a Sergeant or Corporal)
2 CONT • <b>Driver Operator</b> (your father's role)
2 CONT • <b>Gunner</b> (sometimes the commander doubled as gunner in smaller v
2 CONC ehicles)
2 CONT In a larger vehicle like the <b>Staghound Armoured Car</b>, it could be 4 c
2 CONC rew:
2 CONT • Commander
2 CONT • Driver
2 CONT • Gunner
2 CONT • Wireless Operator (sometimes split off)
2 CONT <b>Important:</b>
2 CONT Dad wasn’t just driving — he was <i>the main communication lifeline</i> o
2 CONC f the patrol. If the radio failed, <b>the patrol was blind and isolated
2 CONC </b> — extremely dangerous.
2 CONT <b></b> <b>Postwar Setting (Italy and Egypt)</b>
2 CONT • <b>Italy (1946)</b>:
2 CONT • Reconnaissance patrols across rural and mountainous terrain.
2 CONT • Securing roads, checking bridges, liaising with Italian local forces.
2 CONT • Very mobile, very independent — sometimes operating miles ahead of ma
2 CONC in forces.
2 CONT • <b>Egypt (late 1946–47)</b>:
2 CONT • Desert reconnaissance — harsh driving conditions.
2 CONT • Guarding key British interests (like the Suez Canal and airfields).
2 CONT • Watching political unrest brewing postwar.
2 CONT His job was absolutely critical to keeping operations smooth and safe.
2 CONT <b></b> <b>The Wireless Set No. 19 — A Quick Glance</b>
2 CONT Just for fun, here’s what he probably operated:
2 CONT <b>Feature</b>
2 CONT <b>Detail</b>
2 CONT <b>Frequency</b>
2 CONT Short Wave (High Frequency HF band)
2 CONT <b>Range</b>
2 CONT About 5–15 miles (depending on terrain)
2 CONT <b>Power</b>
2 CONT Valve (vacuum tube) technology
2 CONT <b>Famous for</b>
2 CONT Being reliable but very fiddly to tune!
2 CONT <b></b> <b>Final Thought</b>
2 CONT Dad’s skill set as a <b>Driver Operator</b> made him:
2 CONT • Mechanically skilled
2 CONT • Radio communications savvy
2 CONT • Trained in battlefield tactics
2 CONT • Able to handle the pressure of both movement <i>and</i> command-and-c
2 CONC ontrol under risky conditions
2 CONT Honestly — it wasn’t just a "driver" job — <b>it was specialist recce w
2 CONC ork</b> that required a lot of trust from his officers.
2 CONT <b></b> <b>🇵🇸 British Soldiers in Palestine (1945–1948)</b>
2 CONT During Dads time, <b>Palestine</b> was under <b>British Mandate control
2 CONC </b>, but by 1946–47 it had become <i>extremely volatile</i>:
2 CONT • <b>Jewish paramilitary groups</b> (like Irgun, Haganah, and Lehi) wer
2 CONC e fighting to establish a Jewish state and end British rule.
2 CONT • <b>Arab nationalist groups</b> were also pushing back against Zionist i
2 CONC mmigration and British control.
2 CONT • Britain was stuck in the middle, trying to maintain order until a pol
2 CONC itical solution could be found (which, ultimately, became the creation o
2 CONC f Israel in 1948).
2 CONT This period was called the <b>Palestine Emergency</b>.
2 CONT <b></b> <b>What British Troops Were Doing There</b>
2 CONT Dad's unit, even if based in Egypt, could have been temporarily <b>deta
2 CONC ched</b> or <b>assigned duties in Palestine</b> such as:
2 CONT • <b>Convoy escort</b> — protecting British and civilian transport from a
2 CONC mbushes.
2 CONT • <b>Guard duties</b> — around vital installations like:
2 CONT • Railways
2 CONT • Ports (like Haifa)
2 CONT • Airfields
2 CONT • Government buildings
2 CONT • <b>Patrolling</b> rural areas to suppress armed groups.
2 CONT • <b>Security operations</b> — roadblocks, curfews, searches for weapon
2 CONC s.
2 CONT Because he was <b>in an armoured unit (9th Lancers)</b>, his armoured c
2 CONC ar patrols would have been particularly useful on:
2 CONT • Long dangerous stretches of road
2 CONT • Convoy escort against mines and ambushes
2 CONT • Quick reaction forces after incidents
2 CONT <b></b> <b>Danger Level</b>
2 CONT It wasn’t full-scale war yet, but <b>it was incredibly dangerous</b>:
2 CONT • <b>IEDs (improvised explosives)</b> and mines were common on roads.
2 CONT • <b>Sniper attacks</b> against British soldiers happened frequently.
2 CONT • <b>Terrorist bombings</b> (for example, the King David Hotel bombing i
2 CONC n July 1946).
2 CONT British losses in Palestine in 1946–47 were significant—soldiers like y
2 CONC our father had to be constantly alert, even when just moving between ba
2 CONC ses.
2 CONT <b></b> <b>Summarizing dad's Service Path</b>
2 CONT <b>Year</b>
2 CONT <b>Location</b>
2 CONT <b>Duties</b>
2 CONT 1946
2 CONT Italy (Montabello area)
2 CONT Postwar patrols, security
2 CONT Late 1946
2 CONT Egypt (Suez Zone)
2 CONT Base duties, desert training
2 CONT Late 1946–47
2 CONT Palestine (temporary deployment)
2 CONT Convoy protection, security ops during Palestine Emergency
2 CONT Nov 1947
2 CONT Return to UK aboard H.T. Otranto
2 CONT
2 CONT
2 CONT Dad's service spans a <b>really fascinating, transitional era</b> — fro
2 CONC m the end of WWII into the complicated end of the British Empire.
2 CONT <b></b> <b></b>
2 CONT At some point dad was employed as the Squadron Office Clerk
2 CONT It shows that <b>he was trusted with a lot of responsibility</b>, and t
2 CONC hat <b>his skill set was broader than just the battlefield</b>. Let’s l
2 CONC ook at what that role would have involved, especially in an armoured re
2 CONC connaissance unit like the <b>9th Lancers</b> in the late 1940s.
2 CONT <b></b> <b>Squadron Office Clerk – Duties and Responsibilities</b>
2 CONT A <b>Squadron Office Clerk</b> was like the administrative "heartbeat" o
2 CONC f a squadron — a vital role, even in a mobile armoured unit.
2 CONT Here’s what his work would have involved:
2 CONT <b></b> <b>Administration</b>
2 CONT • Keeping <b>daily records</b>: patrol logs, vehicle movement records, g
2 CONC uard rosters, convoy schedules.
2 CONT • Recording <b>disciplinary matters</b>, <b>leave requests</b>, <b>sick r
2 CONC eports</b>, and <b>reassignments</b>.
2 CONT • Typing and filing <b>orders from HQ</b> and <b>squadron commanders</b
2 CONC >.
2 CONT • <b>Maintaining personnel files</b>: keeping track of who was posted w
2 CONC here, who was promoted, and who was being demobilized.
2 CONT <b></b> <b>Communications</b>
2 CONT • Preparing <b>written reports</b> from patrols and engagements, often w
2 CONC orking directly from radio reports received during operations.
2 CONT • Taking <b>dictation</b> from officers and typing formal correspondenc
2 CONC e to higher headquarters.
2 CONT • Distributing <b>orders</b> received via signal units or messengers.
2 CONT • Organizing <b>convoy movement paperwork</b> (especially important in P
2 CONC alestine where every road movement was vulnerable and had to be careful
2 CONC ly logged).
2 CONT <b></b> <b>Security and Confidentiality</b>
2 CONT • Handling <b>classified information</b>: patrol orders, security notic
2 CONC es, intelligence reports.
2 CONT • Required to maintain strict <b>secrecy</b> about operations — especia
2 CONC lly in politically sensitive areas like Palestine.
2 CONT <b></b> <b>Why It Matters</b>
2 CONT Being made <b>Squadron Office Clerk</b> says several important things a
2 CONC bout dad:
2 CONT • He was <b>very literate and detail-oriented</b> (not always common in t
2 CONC he army back then).
2 CONT • He was <b>highly trusted</b> by officers — you wouldn't hand administ
2 CONC rative control to just anyone.
2 CONT • He had shown <b>leadership and responsibility</b>, even off the battl
2 CONC efield.
2 CONT Often, men who were good Driver-Operators (handling both mechanical and c
2 CONC ommunications duties in the field) were seen as perfect candidates for a
2 CONC dministrative roles later in their service, especially as units wound d
2 CONC own and peacetime routines returned.<b></b> <b>How This Fits into His S
2 CONC tory</b>
2 CONT <b>Timeframe</b>
2 CONT <b>Role</b>
2 CONT <b>Notes</b>
2 CONT Early 1946
2 CONT Driver-Operator
2 CONT Armoured patrols in Italy
2 CONT Late 1946
2 CONT Driver-Operator
2 CONT Egypt, likely desert training and Suez security
2 CONT Late 1946–47
2 CONT Driver-Operator + possibly light patrol duty in Palestine
2 CONT
2 CONT 1947
2 CONT Squadron Office Clerk
2 CONT Managing administration during demobilization, transfer back to UK
2 CONT
2 CONT
2 CONT
2 CONT
2 CONT <b>Timeline Summary for Dad's Service (9th Lancers, 1946-1947)</b>
2 CONT
2 CONT <b>Early 1946 — Italy (Montabello Area)</b>
2 CONT • Role: Driver-Operator
2 CONT • Duties: Armoured car patrols, convoy escort, reconnaissance duties.
2 CONT • Equipment: Humber Scout Car, Daimler Armoured Car.
2 CONT • Skills: Vehicle maintenance, radio communication (Wireless Set No. 19
2 CONC ), navigation.
2 CONT <b>Late 1946 — Egypt (Suez Canal Zone)</b>
2 CONT • Role: Driver-Operator
2 CONT • Duties: Security patrols, convoy movement along desert roads, trainin
2 CONC g exercises.
2 CONT • Base locations: Potentially near Cairo, Ismailia, or Alexandria.
2 CONT <b>Late 1946 - Early 1947 — Palestine (Temporary Posting)</b>
2 CONT • Role: Driver-Operator (and light patrol duties)
2 CONT • Duties: Road security, convoy protection, anti-sabotage patrols durin
2 CONC g the Palestine Emergency.
2 CONT • Danger: Mines, ambushes, political unrest.
2 CONT <b>Mid to Late 1947 — Egypt (Administrative Reassignment)</b>
2 CONT • Role: Squadron Office Clerk
2 CONT • Duties:
2 CONT • Maintaining daily personnel and vehicle records.
2 CONT • Typing orders and official correspondence.
2 CONT • Organizing convoy schedules and patrol logs.
2 CONT • Handling confidential operational documents.
2 CONT • Reason for Change: High trust and proven organizational skills.
2 CONT <b>24 November 1947 — Return to UK</b>
2 CONT • Departure from 156 Transit Camp aboard H.T. Otranto.
2 CONT • Return voyage to Southampton or Liverpool.
2 CONT • Demobilization and end of active service.
2 CONT
2 CONT <b>Squadron Office Organizational Structure (Typical, 1946-47)</b>
2 CONT <b>Squadron Headquarters (SHQ)</b>
2 CONT • Officer Commanding (Major)
2 CONT • Second-in-Command (Captain)
2 CONT • Adjutant/Orderly Room Officer (Lieutenant)
2 CONT • <b>Squadron Office Clerk (Trooper / Lance Corporal)</b> ← <i>(Dad’s r
2 CONC ole)</i>
2 CONT • Signals NCO (communications coordinator)
2 CONT • Quartermaster Sergeant (equipment and supplies)
2 CONT <b>Main Responsibilities of Squadron Office Clerk:</b>
2 CONT • Filing and maintaining personnel documents.
2 CONT • Keeping patrol, convoy, and leave records up to date.
2 CONT • Issuing and logging written orders.
2 CONT • Supporting squadron staff with operational communication.
2 CONT • Managing confidential reports and correspondence.
2 CONT
2 CONT This shows how Dad's role evolved from a technical, frontline recce spe
2 CONC cialist to a highly trusted administrative backbone for the squadron as t
2 CONC he army transitioned out of active conflict.
2 CONT
2 CONT <b></b> <b>🪖 Patrol Example (Typical 3-Car Troop)</b>
2 CONT <b>Vehicle Number</b>
2 CONT <b>Crew</b>
2 CONT <b>Role</b>
2 CONT <b>1</b>
2 CONT Troop Leader (Sergeant or Corporal), Driver-Operator, Gunner
2 CONT Lead / command vehicle
2 CONT 2
2 CONT 2nd-in-line, relays and support
2 CONT Supporting fire and comms
2 CONT 3
2 CONT Tail-end, covers rear
2 CONT Last line, also watches flanks and rear threats
2 CONT
