3 CONT <b>🚢 H.T. Otranto – The Troopship</b>
3 CONT <b>H.T. Otranto</b> (short for <i>Hired Transport Otranto</i>) was a <b
3 CONC >British troopship</b> operated postwar by the Ministry of Transport. O
3 CONC riginally a passenger liner, it was used extensively in the 1940s to fe
3 CONC rry troops and returning personnel between overseas bases and the UK.
3 CONT By late 1947, it was doing regular runs from:
3 CONT •
3 CONT <b>Middle East</b> (Egypt, Suez Canal Zone)
3 CONT •
3 CONT <b>Far East</b>
3 CONT •
3 CONT <b>India</b> ...back to <b>Southampton</b> or <b>Liverpool</b>.
3 CONT So this ship was one of the main arteries bringing men like your father h
3 CONC ome as Britain wound down its imperial military presence.<b>🛏️ 156 T/C
3 CONC amp – Transit Camp (likely Egypt)</b>
3 CONT The “<b>156 Transit Camp</b>” was likely one of the <b>demobilization s
3 CONC taging camps</b> in Egypt, probably near <b>Port Said</b> or <b>Tel el K
3 CONC ebir</b>, both of which were major British military hubs at the time.
3 CONT These camps handled:
3 CONT •
3 CONT Final paperwork
3 CONT •
3 CONT Medical checks
3 CONT •
3 CONT Kit turn-in
3 CONT •
3 CONT Issue of travel documents
3 CONT •
3 CONT Waiting for space on returning ships like the Otranto
3 CONT This would have been the final stretch before your father boarded ship, a
3 CONC fter which it was a <b>sea journey of about 10–14 days</b> depending on t
3 CONC he route.<b>📜 Historical Vibe: November 1947</b>
3 CONT To put this in context:
3 CONT •
3 CONT Britain was beginning to <b>pull out of Palestine</b> (huge tensions th
3 CONC ere at the time)
3 CONT •
3 CONT The Cold War was brewing
3 CONT •
3 CONT Nationalist movements were pushing hard across Egypt
3 CONT •
3 CONT British demobilization was winding down, but <b>thousands of troops</b> w
3 CONC ere still coming home
3 CONT Your father’s return in <b>late 1947</b> places him among the <b>last m
3 CONC ajor waves of demobbed WWII servicemen</b> still on overseas duty—he se
3 CONC rved well beyond VJ Day, which adds to the significance of his service.
