3 CONC e to King Edward Court from Peascod Street. It had been a thriving busi
3 CONC ness numbering among its customers the main hotels and King Edward’s Ho
3 CONC spital. It was finally demolished to make way for the King Edward Court d
3 CONC evelopment.
3 CONT When he undertook the survey in 1958, the architect made the drawing of t
3 CONC he back view of the premises, shown here, and he describes what he saw a
3 CONC t that time. His comments provide a vivid picture of the working condit
3 CONC ions of those employed in the ramshackle building which by then had str
3 CONC uctural cracks through which daylight could be seen.
3 CONT ‘On the top of the old four-storey block there is a small tree growing f
3 CONC rom the rotten and sodden brickwork. Just in front of that is a corruga
3 CONC ted iron shed and sheet stall smoke stack for the large old coke-fired b
3 CONC oiler, which fed hot water into the building through the lagged pipe th
3 CONC at can be seen bending out of the right-hand side of the tin shed. Behi
3 CONC nd the shed, under the timber shoreing holding it up, can be seen the b
3 CONC oilerman stoker cooling off with a cigarette. The door to the boiler ro
3 CONC om is set open to cool off the stoke hole. To the top right of the pict
3 CONC ure is a second floor office and, very properly, a fire escape route fr
3 CONC om it was provided. This consisted of a ladder laid diagonally across a
3 CONC n asbestos cement sheeted roof, complete with handrail on bracket suppo
3 CONC rts and a vertical wooden ladder set buttress-wise against the adjacent s
3 CONC heeted building. Note the washstand mirror, with carved cherrywood surr
3 CONC ound, carefully propped at the top of this ladder. This enabled the sto
3 CONC ker of the boiler to see the top of the boiler chimney from inside the b
3 CONC oiler house when it was raining, and judge from the colour and amount o
3 CONC f the smoke, the state of the boiler and whether it required attention o
3 CONC r not.
3 CONT From the double doors at the foot of the ladder can be seen emerging a s
3 CONC tream of dirty soapy water. The drains in the area could not take this o
3 CONC utflow, so it flooded the yard and soaked into the ground. The holes an
3 CONC d hollows produced were filled up with ash and clinker from the boiler. T
3 CONC o the right of the picture there is an old car rusting away in a danger
3 CONC ous garage, and someone is throwing laundry boxes out of a van. There i
3 CONC s no insulation in the place and little more than natural ventilation. J
3 CONC ust above the ladder is a rickety ventilation duct made of old tins riv
3 CONC eted together, between the windows which lit the ironing and finishing a
3 CONC rea.’
3 CONT <b>Michael A. A. Bayley</b>
3 CONT (<i>Web editor’s note September 2023: In the summer of 1966, The Ricky-
3 CONC Tick club was due to be turfed out of the old TA premises they used by t
3 CONC he river at Clewer Mead. A newspaper article around July 1966, details t
3 CONC he possible move to part of the old Windsor Steam Laundry. John Mansfie
3 CONC ld, in his book, ‘As You Were : The True Adventures of the Ricky Tick c
3 CONC lub’ tells of the problems he had trying to get council permission for h
3 CONC is club.</i> <i>But, maybe it was just as well, as the state of the bui
3 CONC lding sounds worse than Clewer Mead !)</i>
