1 NOTE Albert Edward Vickers was born on 20th March 1890, youngest son of Henr
2 CONC y and Eliza Vickers.
2 CONT
2 CONT From the 1901 Census, Albert was 11 years old and probably still a scho
2 CONC lar, at this time he was living with his parents, at 61 Victoria Cottag
2 CONC es (formally Edwards Square), along with brothers James and Arthur and s
2 CONC ister Ellen.
2 CONT By 1911, Albert was a Butcher, living at 16 Victoria Cottages.
2 CONT By 1915 Albert had enlisted and was a Seargent with the Royal Rifles, S
2 CONC ervice number S2703, and was part of the Machine Gun Corps.
2 CONT
2 CONT 22nd December 1917, Albert is recorded as being in Hosptial in Kent, ha
2 CONC ving been wounded in the chest and Arm. [full details not known current
2 CONC ly]
2 CONT
2 CONT Albert was awarded the Military Medal on 24/04/1918 This Level 3 Gallan
2 CONC try Medal was established during the First World War on the 25th March 1
2 CONC 916 and introduced in the London Gazette issue 29525 (back dated to 191
2 CONC 4) to personnel of the British Army and other services, and personnel o
2 CONC f Commonwealth countries, below commissioned rank. It was the other ran
2 CONC ks' equivalent to the Military Cross (M.C.), (which was awarded to Comm
2 CONC issioned Officers and, rarely, to Warrant Officers, who could also be a
2 CONC warded the M.M.)
2 CONT
2 CONT The military decoration was awarded to A.E.Vickers for acts of gallantr
2 CONC y and devotion to duty under fire or for individual or associated acts o
2 CONC f bravery which were insufficient to merit the Distinguished Conduct Me
2 CONC dal.
2 CONT
2 CONT Conferment of the medal was announced in the London Gazette and A.E.Vic
2 CONC kers earned the right to add the letters M.M. to his name.
2 CONT
2 CONT Between 20th April and 28th April 1918, Albert was in Villiers Bretonne
2 CONC ux. Below is the War Diary report for those days for the 2nd Battalion o
2 CONC f the "The Rifles Brigade".
2 CONT
2 CONT 19-04-1918 Companies under Os.C.Coys for Gas Drill Musketry and Squad D
2 CONC rill. The Battalion (less detail) moved from <b>CAMON</b> to billets at <
2 CONC b>BLANGY TRONVILLE.</b> 20-04-1918 The Battalion relieved elements of t
2 CONC he 55th & 56th Battalions of the 14th Australian Brigade, “B” Company f
2 CONC ront line – (left), “C” Company front line – (right) “A” Company Suppor
2 CONC t<u>, “D” Company Reserve</u>. The night was exceedingly quiet and the r
2 CONC elief was carried out without casualty. 21-04-1918 Very quiet day. No c
2 CONC asualties. A considerable amount of work was done improving posts and c
2 CONC onstructing a continuous apron of wire in front of front line. 22-04-19
2 CONC 18 A very quiet day. No casualties. Work as on 21st. “A” Company took o
2 CONC ver one company front on the right up to, but not including the <b>VILL
2 CONC IERS BRETONNEUX WARFUSEE Road</b> from one company 2 East Lancs. Regt. t
2 CONC his relief was carried out without casualties. Lieutenant Colonel H.S.C
2 CONC . Richardson took over command of the Battalion vice Lieutenant Colonel R
2 CONC . A. Mostyn-Owen posted to Command 13th Battalion The Riffle Brigade. 2
2 CONC 3-04-1918 24-04-1918 A Patrol, consisting of 2 Lt P.G. McCubbin and oth
2 CONC er ranks left our lines at 2am 23rd inst to reconnoitre the right of ou
2 CONC r front. One Rifleman, wounded, reported at Battalion Headquarters at a
2 CONC bout 3am that 2nd Lt. McCubbin had been wounded, also some members of t
2 CONC he Patrol. Another Patrol was immediately sent out, no trace the first p
2 CONC atrol, which seems to have walked into an enemy post, could be found. 2 u
2 CONC nwounded members of the first patrol eventually returned to our lines. 2
2 CONC nd Lt. McCubbin was “Missing”. 2nd Lt. J. Farrell joined for duty. Repo
2 CONC rts received that enemy would attach at dawn obtained from prisoners ca
2 CONC ptured on the right of our sector. No attack developed, probably owing t
2 CONC o wet morning. A quiet day. Work done improving our line and wiring pos
2 CONC ts continued. A new MG post made in our line near Battalion Headquarter
2 CONC s. Some enemy gas shells at night. Reports again received late that ene
2 CONC my would attack at dawn on 24th. Enemy observed working in <b>VILLIERS B
2 CONC RETONNEUX – WARFUSEE Road,</b> fired on by our Lewis guns and rifles fr
2 CONC om our line. Reported to Division by Brigade Major. Heavy enemy barrage c
2 CONC ame down at 3.45am. This continues until about 7am, when it became less i
2 CONC ntense, and chiefly covered ground between Reserve line and Battalion H
2 CONC eadquarters. Barrage included a large proportion of Gas Shells. Continu
2 CONC al reports received from Os.C. Companies that barrage was not on Front L
2 CONC ine or Close support Companies during the above hours. During the night 2
2 CONC 3/24th ½ D Company had been moved into close support on the right and h
2 CONC alf on the left by order of G.O.C. 25th Infantry Brigade. The morning w
2 CONC as very misty and  the enemy put down a heavy smoke barrage at dawn, ma
2 CONC king it impossible to see for more than 20 yards. About 7am a runner fo
2 CONC rm “A” Company reported at Battalion Headquarters that the enemy had go
2 CONC t round the right flank of the company, and was attacking them and the s
2 CONC upport platoons of <u>“D” Company </u>from flank and rear, and was movi
2 CONC ng towards “C” Company. At 8am “B” Company was ordered to form a defens
2 CONC ive flank, joining with support platoons of <u>“D” company </u>and rema
2 CONC ins of “C” Company, from “B” Company’s right to reserve line. Battalion H
2 CONC Q details moved forward to continue the line covering Battn. Headquarte
2 CONC rs and in touch with 2nd R. Berkshire Regt. on the right, N.W. of <b>VI
2 CONC LLIERS-BRETONNEUX</b>. 2nd Lt. Gurrier and elements of A C & D Coys joi
2 CONC ned this line during the morning. At 9am enemy Very Lights were seen go
2 CONC ing up on N.W. outskirts of <b>VILLIERS-BRETONNEUX </b>and enemy machin
2 CONC e guns opened fire on vicinity of Bn. Headquarters. Reserve line and vi
2 CONC cinity of new line joining with 2nd Royal Berkshire Regt. was shelled a
2 CONC t intervals all day. B Company on the left was subjected to heavy trenc
2 CONC h Mortar fire at intervals, the enemy advanced several times on the rig
2 CONC ht of this company, but each time driven off by rifle and machine gun f
2 CONC ire. It was afterwards ascertained that the enemy, after breaking throu
2 CONC gh <b>SOUTH of VILLIERS BRETONNEUX – WARFUSEE Road,</b> had turned in N
2 CONC orthwards, between our front line and support lines and also in rear of t
2 CONC he latter, being unobserved owing to the dense mist and smoke barrage. A & C C
2 CONC ompanies taken unawares in the rear were overwhelmed after a sharp figh
2 CONC t by superior numbers of the enemy, the whole of the two Companies with f
2 CONC ew exceptions being killed or captured. Very little was ascertained as t
2 CONC o their exact fate, but it is known that one Platoon of D Coy. fought t
2 CONC o their last man, as was completely wiped out. 2nd Lt. Doyle, was dange
2 CONC rously wounded while commanding this Platoon, was found on the night of t
2 CONC he 24/25th during the counter-attack by the Australians. The remainder o
2 CONC f the day passed without further attacks on our front , with the except
2 CONC ion of half-hearted attempts to turn the right flank of B Company which w
2 CONC ere frustrated by the effective fire , brought to bear on them by this c
2 CONC ompany. On the night of 24/25th a counter-attack on <b>VILLIERS BRETONN
2 CONC EUX </b>and ground SW of the village, was carried out by a Australian B
2 CONC rigade, which surrounded the village, establishing itself on the Easter
2 CONC n outskirts as far as the Old Hangars on the<b> VILLIERS BRETONNEUX WAR
2 CONC FUSEE Road</b>, with its right flank thrown back. Its left covered the N
2 CONC orthern and North Western parts of the village, and was extended to eth r
2 CONC ight flank of our B Company, where this Company bent back, forming our d
2 CONC efensive flank. The Australians left at this time was not in touch with B C
2 CONC ompany’s right, but the gap was covered by the continuation of our line j
2 CONC oining up with the 2nd Royal Berkshire Regt. Our lines were shelled at i
2 CONC ntervals throughout the night. 25-04-1918 The lines held by the Battali
2 CONC on were not attacked on the 25th inst. Readjustments of our lines were c
2 CONC arried out early on night 25/26th. B Company front line, 2 Platoons of <
2 CONC u>D Company </u>in Support in positions occupied by A Company when the l
2 CONC ine was taken over. <u>1 Platoon of D Company </u>and an amalgamated Pl
2 CONC atoon formed of remains of A & C Coys in Reserve in Old Reserve Line. O
2 CONC n night 25/26th the Battalion moved to counter-attack positions W. of <
2 CONC b>VILLIERS BRETONNEUX</b>. 26-04-1918 Situation on the S.E. outskirts o
2 CONC f <b>VILLIERS BRETONNEUX</b> being obscure, orders received from Divisi
2 CONC on were brought to Battalion Headquarters  by Brigade Major, 25th Infan
2 CONC try Brigade that a reconnaissance was to be carried out to clear this p
2 CONC art of the village if necessary,  and make sure of the situation. This w
2 CONC as carried out by 2 Platoons of B Company under 2nd Lt. McGee, accompan
2 CONC ied by the Brigade Major, 25th Infantry Brigade, who carried out the re
2 CONC connaissance meeting with considerable resistance outside the village. S
2 CONC everal casualties were inflicted on the enemy, 2 machine gun teams bein
2 CONC g put out of action by our fire. The Party returned at 2pm, having suff
2 CONC ered casualties – 2nd Lt. McGee killed – 26 other ranks killed and woun
2 CONC ded. The rest of the day passed without further incident. 27-04-1918 A q
2 CONC uiet day. The Battalion remained in counter-attack position and was not c
2 CONC alled upon to take part in active operations. Casualties Nil. Casualtie
2 CONC s Sustained by Battalion between 23/26th April. 1 Officer Killed – 3 Of
2 CONC ficers wounded – 2 Officers wounded & missing – 9 Officers Missing – Ot
2 CONC her ranks . Killed 18 – Wounded  96 – Missing 268 28-04-1918 At 10am. o
2 CONC rders were received to evacuate the position occupied by the Battalion a
2 CONC nd the Battalion moved by march route to billets at <b>BOUTILIERE</b>, S
2 CONC . of <b>AMIENS</b>.
2 CONT
2 CONT 27th May 1918, Albert and his Company were taken Prison at <b>Juvincour
2 CONC t,</b> They had been surrounded by the enemy and had run out of ammunit
2 CONC ion. They were held at a Camp at <b>Cassel</b> until 6th June 1918, whe
2 CONC n they were moved to the Camp at <b>Crossen a/oder </b>in Poland, some 6
2 CONC 00 miles away. The arrived at this camp on 8th October 1918
2 CONT
2 CONT Albert was repatriated to the UK, sometime after 11 November 1918, alth
2 CONC ough at this time records of this event cannot be found.
2 CONT
2 CONT Albert would have also been awarded the Victory Medal and the Star.
2 CONT
