1 EVEN Sergeant -10th Battalion The Rifle Brigade (Prince Consorts Own)
2 TYPE military service
2 DATE 1914
2 NOTE <b>First World WarRegular army</b>
3 CONT The 1st Battalion landed at Le Havre as part of the 11th Brigade in the 4
3 CONC th Division in August 1914 for service on the Western Front.[31] The ba
3 CONC ttalion saw action at the First Battle of the Marne in September 1914, t
3 CONC he First Battle of the Aisne in September 1914 and the Battle of Messin
3 CONC es in October 1914 as well as the Second Battle of Ypres in April 1915, t
3 CONC he Battle of the Somme in Autumn 1916 and the Battle of Arras in April 1
3 CONC 917 before taking part in the Battle of Passchendaele in Autumn 1917, t
3 CONC he Battle of the Lys in April 1918, the Advance in Flanders, the Second B
3 CONC attle of the Somme in August 1918, the battles of the Hindenburg Line a
3 CONC nd the Final Advance in Picardy.[32]
3 CONT The 2nd Battalion landed at Le Havre as part of the 25th Brigade in the 8
3 CONC th Division in November 1914 for service on the Western Front.[31] The b
3 CONC attalion saw action at the Battle of Neuve Chapelle in March 1915, the B
3 CONC attle of Aubers Ridge in May 1915 and the Battle of the Somme in Autumn 1
3 CONC 916 as well as the advance to the Hindenburg Line, the Battle of Pilcke
3 CONC m Ridge in August 1917 and the Battle of Passchendaele in Autumn 1917 b
3 CONC efore taking part in the Battle of St Quentin in March 1918, the Battle o
3 CONC f Rosieres in March 1918, the Third Battle of the Aisne in May 1918, th
3 CONC e Battle of the Scarpe in August 1918 and the Final Advance in Artois.[
3 CONC 33]
3 CONT The 3rd Battalion landed at Saint-Nazaire as part of the 17th Brigade i
3 CONC n the 6th Division in September 1914 for service on the Western Front.[
3 CONC 31] The battalion saw action at the Battle of Delville Wood in July 191
3 CONC 6, the Battle of Guillemont in September 1916 and the Battle of Vimy Ri
3 CONC dge in April 1917 as well as the Battle of Messines in June 1917, the B
3 CONC attle of Passchendaele in October 1917 and the Battle of Cambrai in Nov
3 CONC ember 1917 before taking part in the Second Battle of the Somme in Augu
3 CONC st 1918, the Battle of Cambrai in October 1918 and the Final Advance in P
3 CONC icardy.[34]
3 CONT The 4th Battalion landed at Le Havre as part of the 80th Brigade in the 2
3 CONC 7th Division in December 1914 for service on the Western Front but move
3 CONC d to Salonika in November 1915.[31]<b>Territorial force</b>
3 CONT The 18th (London) Battalion, 19th (Western) Battalion, 20th (Northern) B
3 CONC attalion, 21st (Midland) Battalion, 22nd (Wessex & Welsh) Battalion, 23
3 CONC rd (North Western) Battalion and 24th (Home Counties) Battalion were al
3 CONC l post overseas on garrison duties in 1916.[31]<b>New armies</b>
3 CONT The 7th (Service) Battalion and 8th (Service) Battalion landed at Boulo
3 CONC gne-sur-Mer as part of the 41st Brigade in the 14th (Light) Division in M
3 CONC ay 1915 for service on the Western Front.[31] The 8th Battalion took pa
3 CONC rt in the Second Battle of Ypres, which had begun on 22 April 1915 and t
3 CONC he action at Hooge in July 1915 where they saw the first use of flameth
3 CONC rowers by the Germans.[35] Second Lieutenant Sidney Woodroffe, of the 8
3 CONC th Battalion, was awarded the Victoria Cross for his actions in this ba
3 CONC ttle.[36] The battalions also saw action in the Second Battle of Ypres w
3 CONC hich had begun in April 1915 and an action near La Brique in Belgium wh
3 CONC ere Corporal Alfred George Drake, also of the 8th Battalion, was posthu
3 CONC mously awarded the Victoria Cross for his actions on 23 November 1915.[
3 CONC 37] The battalions then took part in the Battle of Delville Wood in Sep
3 CONC tember 1916, the Battle of Flers–Courcelette in September 1916 and the a
3 CONC dvance to the Hindenburg Line as well as the Battle of Arras in April 1
3 CONC 917, the Battle of Langemark in August 1917 and the Battle of Passchend
3 CONC aele in October 1917 before taking part in the Battle of St Quentin in M
3 CONC arch 1918 and the Battle of the Avre in April 1918.[38][39]
3 CONT The 9th (Service) Battalion landed at Boulogne-sur-Mer as part of the 4
3 CONC 2nd Brigade in the 14th (Light) Division in May 1915 for service on the W
3 CONC estern Front[31] and took part in most of the same battles as the 7th a
3 CONC nd 8th battalions.[40]
3 CONT The 10th (Service) Battalion and 11th (Service) Battalion landed at Bou
3 CONC logne-sur-Mer as part of the 59th Brigade in the 20th (Light) Division i
3 CONC n July 1915 for service on the Western Front.[31] The battalions saw ac
3 CONC tion at the Battle of Mont Sorrel in June 1916, the Battle of Delville W
3 CONC ood in September 1916 and the Battle of Guillemont in September 1916 as w
3 CONC ell as the Battle of Flers–Courcelette in September 1916, the Battle of M
3 CONC orval in September 1916 and the Battle of Le Transloy in October 1916 b
3 CONC efore taking part in the advance to the Hindenburg Line, the Battle of L
3 CONC angemarck in August 1917, the Battle of the Menin Road Ridge in Septemb
3 CONC er 1917, the Battle of Polygon Wood in September 1917 and the Battle of C
3 CONC ambrai in December 1917.[41][42]
3 CONT The 12th (Service) Battalion landed at Boulogne-sur-Mer as part of the 6
3 CONC 0th Brigade in the 20th (Light) Division in July 1915 for service on th
3 CONC e Western Front[31] and took part in most of the same battles as the 10
3 CONC th and 11th battalions. The 12th battalion also took part in the action a
3 CONC t Pietre, part of a subsidiary attack on the 25th of September 1915 dur
3 CONC ing the battle of Loos where it advanced along in support of the Indian C
3 CONC orps. The battalion made good ground but retired when the units on both i
3 CONC ts flanks were forced back and it lost many many killed, wounded and mi
3 CONC ssing during this withdrawal.[43]
3 CONT The 13th (Service) Battalion landed at Boulogne-sur-Mer as part of the 1
3 CONC 11th Brigade in the 37th Division in July 1915 for service on the Weste
3 CONC rn Front.[31] The battalion saw action at the Battle of the Somme in Su
3 CONC mmer 1916 and the advance to the Hindenburg Line as well as the Battle o
3 CONC f Arras in April 1917, the Battle of Passchendaele in Autumn 1917 and t
3 CONC he Battle of Cambrai in November 1917 before taking part in the Battle o
3 CONC f the Lys in April 1918, the Third Battle of the Aisne in May 1918, the S
3 CONC econd Battle of the Somme in August 1918, the Battles of the Hindenburg L
3 CONC ine and the Final Advance in Picardy.[44]
3 CONT The 16th (Service) Battalion (St Pancras) landed at Le Havre as part of t
3 CONC he 117th Brigade in the 39th Division in March 1916 for service on the W
3 CONC estern Front.[31] The battalion saw action at the Battle of the Somme i
3 CONC n Autumn 1916, the Battle of Pilckem Ridge in August 1917 and the Battl
3 CONC e of Langemarck in August 1917 as well as the Battle of the Menin Road R
3 CONC idge in September 1917, the Battle of Polygon Wood in September 1917 an
3 CONC d the Second Battle of Passchendaele in November 1917 before taking par
3 CONC t in the Battle of St Quentin in March 1918 and the Second Battle of Ba
3 CONC paume in August 1918.[45]
