2 _SENT The Second Battle of Villers-Bretonneux (also Actions of Villers-Breton
3 CONC neux, after the First Battles of the Somme, 1918) took place from 24 to 2
3 CONC 7 April 1918, during the German spring offensive to the east of Amiens. I
3 CONC t is notable for being the first occasion on which tanks fought against e
3 CONC ach other; it was the biggest and most successful tank action of the Ge
3 CONC rman army in the First World War.
3 CONT Three German A7Vs engaged three British Mark IV tanks, two of which wer
3 CONC e female tanks armed only with machine-guns. The two Mark IV females we
3 CONC re damaged and forced to withdraw but the male tank, armed with 6-pound
3 CONC er guns, hit and disabled the lead A7V, which was then abandoned by its c
3 CONC rew. The Mark IV continued to fire on the two remaining German A7Vs, wh
3 CONC ich withdrew. The "male" then advanced with the support of several Whip
3 CONC pet light tanks which had arrived, until disabled by artillery fire and a
3 CONC bandoned by the crew.
3 CONT A counter-attack by two Australian brigades and a British brigade durin
3 CONC g the night of 24 April partly surrounded Villers-Bretonneux and on 25 A
3 CONC pril the town was recaptured. On 26 April, the role of the Moroccan div
3 CONC ision of the French army was crucial in pushing back German units. Aust
3 CONC ralian, British and French troops had almost restored the original fron
3 CONC t line by 27 April.
3 CONT Villers-Bretonneux - where Australian and British forces defended again
3 CONC st a German invasion, as well as the follow-up attack only three weeks l
3 CONC ater. Villers-Bretonneux was a desirable point of advantage for both si
3 CONC des of the battle because it was less than 20km from the British transp
3 CONC ort hub, where if the Germans advanced, they could be overthrown by the i
3 CONC nfantry.BattleGerman 2nd Army attack
3 CONT On 17/18 April, the Germans bombarded the area behind Villers-Bretonneu
3 CONC x with mustard gas, causing 1,000 Australian casualties. On the evening o
3 CONC f 23/24 April, an artillery barrage was fired, using mustard gas and hi
3 CONC gh explosive rounds. Next morning, the Germans attacked the village wit
3 CONC h four divisions. The German infantry, with thirteen supporting A7V tan
3 CONC ks, broke through the 8th division, making a 3-mile (4.8 km) wide gap i
3 CONC n the Allied line.[4] Villers-Bretonneux fell to the Germans and the ra
3 CONC ilway junction of Amiens became vulnerable to capture. After the German
3 CONC s took Villers-Bretonneux, the first engagement between opposing tanks t
3 CONC ook place. Three British Mark IV tanks from No. 1 Section, A Company, 1
3 CONC st Battalion, Tank Corps had been dispatched to the Cachy switch line, a
3 CONC t the first reports of German advance and were to hold it against the G
3 CONC ermans.[6] One was a "male" (the No. 1 Tank of the section) armed with t
3 CONC wo 6-pounder guns and machine guns, under the command of Lieutenant Fra
3 CONC nk Mitchell. It was crewed by only four of the normal crew of eight, as t
3 CONC he others had been gassed. The other tanks were "females" armed with 0.
3 CONC 303 in (7.7 mm) machine-guns, for use against infantry. All were advanc
3 CONC ing when they encountered a German A7V, "Nixe" of Abteilung III Imperia
3 CONC l German Tank Force, commanded by 2nd Lieutenant Wilhelm Biltz.
3 CONT Nixe fired on the two "females", damaging them to the extent that it le
3 CONC ft holes in the hull leaving the crew exposed. Both retreated; their ma
3 CONC chine guns were unable to penetrate the armour on the German tank. Mitc
3 CONC hell's "male" Mark IV continued to fire at the A7V, while on the move t
3 CONC o avoid German artillery fire and the gun of the German tank. The movem
3 CONC ent meant Mitchell's gunner had difficulty in aiming the 6-pounders. Th
3 CONC e tanks fired at each other on the move, until the Mark IV stopped to a
3 CONC llow the gunner a clear shot and the gunner scored three hits (a total o
3 CONC f six shell hits).Nixe heeled over on its side, possibly as a result of c
3 CONC rossing an incline at the wrong angle. The surviving German crew (out o
3 CONC f 18 men), including Biltz, alighted from the vehicle and the B ritish f
3 CONC ired at them as they fled on foot, killing nine.
3 CONT The British tank was next faced by two more A7Vs, supported by infantry
3 CONC ; Mitchell's tank fired several ranging shots at the German tanks and t
3 CONC hey retreated. Mitchell's tank continued to attack the German infantry, f
3 CONC iring case-shot. Seven of the new British Whippet medium tanks arrived, a
3 CONC ttacked the Germans, encountered some battalions "forming up in the ope
3 CONC n" and killed many infantry with their machine-guns and by running them d
3 CONC own. Mitchell later remarked that when they returned their tracks were c
3 CONC overed with blood. Only four of the seven Whippets came back, the rest w
3 CONC ere destroyed by artillery and five crew were killed.
3 CONT Being the last tank on the field and slow moving, the Mark IV became a t
3 CONC arget for German artillery and Mitchell ordered the tank back, manoeuvr
3 CONC ing to try to avoid the shells but a mortar round disabled the tracks. T
3 CONC he crew left the tank, escaping to a British-held trench, much to the s
3 CONC urprise of the troops in it. Leutnant Biltz and his crew re-boarded "Ni
3 CONC xe" and attempted to return to their base, but had to abandon the vehic
3 CONC le again when the engines failed. Attempts by the Germans to recover it w
3 CONC ere unsuccessful, and it was blown up by a demolition crew during the n
3 CONC ight of April 23–24. Earlier in the day, another A7V, No 506 "Mephisto"
3 CONC , became ditched in a crater and was abandoned by its crew. It was reco
3 CONC vered by British and Australian troops some three months later, and is n
3 CONC ow held at the Queensland Museum.Fourth Army counter-attack
3 CONT About noon the 1st Battalion of the Sherwood Foresters had attempted a c
3 CONC ounter-attack. The British 25th Brigade was considered for an attack bu
3 CONC t this was cancelled. A tank with troops from the 2nd Royal Berkshire R
3 CONC egiment made a spontaneous attack from the north, pushing the German li
3 CONC ne back about 150 yards (140 m). General Henry Rawlinson had responded e
3 CONC ven before he received orders from Marshal Ferdinand Foch to recapture t
3 CONC he town. At 9:30 a.m. he ordered an immediate counter-attack by the Aus
3 CONC tralian 13th Brigade under Brigadier General Thomas William Glasgow and t
3 CONC he 15th Brigade under Brigadier General H. E. "Pompey" Elliott, both in r
3 CONC eserve, though the 13th Brigade had suffered many casualties at Dernanc
3 CONC ourt nearby. Rawlinson intended an enveloping attack, the 15th Brigade a
3 CONC ttacking north of the town and the 13th Brigade attacking to the south. B
3 CONC ritish troops would support and the 2nd Battalion, Northamptonshire Reg
3 CONC iment and the 22nd Durham Light Infantry would follow through in the ga
3 CONC p between the Australians and "mop up" the town, once it was isolated. A
3 CONC rtillery support was available but since German positions were unknown a
3 CONC nd to avoid alerting the Germans, there was no preparatory barrage to s
3 CONC often up the German positions. Instead the artillery would bombard the t
3 CONC own for the hour once the attack began and then move its line of fire b
3 CONC ack beyond the line held by the Allies before the German attack.
3 CONT Meanwhile, the 14th Brigade held its positions to the north, and provid
3 CONC ed guides to the 15th Brigade. The attack took place on the night of 24
3 CONC /25 April, after a postponement from 8:00 p.m. Glasgow argued that it w
3 CONC ould still be light, with terrible consequences for his men and that th
3 CONC e operation should start at 10:00 p.m. and "zero hour" was eventually s
3 CONC et for 10:00 p.m. The operation began with German machine gun crews cau
3 CONC sing many Australian casualties. A number of charges against machine-gu
3 CONC n posts helped the Australian advance; in particular, Lieutenant Cliffo
3 CONC rd Sadlier of the 51st Battalion, was awarded the Victoria Cross, after a
3 CONC ttacking with hand-grenades. The two brigades swept around Villers-Bret
3 CONC onneux and the Germans retreated, for a while escaping the pocket along a r
3 CONC ailway cutting. The Australians eventually captured the German position
3 CONC s and pushed the German line back, leaving the German troops in Villers
3 CONC -Bretonneux surrounded. The British units attacked frontally and suffer
3 CONC ed many casualties. By 25 April, the town had been recaptured and hande
3 CONC d back to the villagers. The battle was a great success for the Allies, w
3 CONC ho had defeated the German attempt to capture Amiens and recaptured Vil
3 CONC lers-Bretonneux while outnumbered; the village remained in Allied hands t
3 CONC o the end of the war.Role of the Moroccan Division
3 CONT According to Romain Fathi, in New Directions in War and History, the ro
3 CONC le of the Moroccan Division at the Second Battle of Villers-Bretonneux h
3 CONC as been neglected by Australian popular historians. On 26 April, the Fr
3 CONC ench Moroccan Division attacked south of the town and rescued the Austr
3 CONC alian 51st and 52nd Battalions.
3 CONT The personal diaries of journalist Charles Bean and a later account of t
3 CONC he battle by the commanding officer of the 52nd Battalion, Lt. Colonel J
3 CONC . L. Whitham describe myriad problems arising from this being the first t
3 CONC ime the Australians and French had fought together on the Western Front
3 CONC . In particular, with the way each defended newly occupied ground and i
3 CONC n the manner that the French expected to undertake relief of the Austra
3 CONC lian line.
3 CONT While costly, the attack of the Moroccan division was a success, pushin
3 CONC g the line further east than Australian troops had due to the strong Ge
3 CONC rman resistance they had encountered. The Moroccan Division's contribut
3 CONC ion to Second Villers-Bretonneux was crucial to the success of the whol
3 CONC e operation. For its engagement, the 8e régiment de marche de zouaves o
3 CONC f the Moroccan division was awarded a Légion d’honneur by the French Pr
3 CONC esident with the following citation: "The year 1918 finds them ready, o
3 CONC nce again, for all acts of boldness and all sacrifices. On 26 April the
3 CONC y attacked Villers-Bretonneux and blocked the road to Amiens".Aftermath
3 CONC Analysis
3 CONT Villers-Bretonneux - where Australian and British forces defended again
3 CONC st a German invasion, as well as the follow-up attack only three weeks l
3 CONC ater. Villers-Bretonneux was a desirable point of advantage for both si
3 CONC des of the battle because it was less than 20km from the British transp
3 CONC ort hub, where if the Germans advanced, they could be overthrown by the i
3 CONC nfantry.Casualties
3 CONT The fighting around Villers-Bretonneux in April resulted in the followi
3 CONC ng Allied casualties: the Australian brigades had taken 2,473 casualtie
3 CONC s, British casualties were 9,529 and French losses were c. 3,500. Germa
3 CONC n losses were 8,000–10,400 men.
3 CONT
3 CONT The Australian view:- web site - https://www.awmlondon.gov.au/battles/v
3 CONC illers-bretonneux
3 CONT
3 CONT  Villers Bretonneux The End of the German Advance, 1918
3 CONT The Battle in Brief
3 CONT
3 CONT On 21 March 1918, reinforced with divisions from the Eastern Front, the G
3 CONC ermans launched a great offensive against the British forces which with
3 CONC drew across the 1916 Somme battlefield towards the major city of Amiens
3 CONC . The Australian units were hurried south to help hold back the German a
3 CONC dvance north of the Somme at Dernancourt and Morlancourt. However Germa
3 CONC n engineers had extended rail communications south of the Somme towards V
3 CONC illers-Bretonneux, close to the key city of Amiens. If the Germans coul
3 CONC d capture Villers-Bretonneux and reach the edge of a plateau, Amiens wo
3 CONC uld be within range of their artillery.
3 CONT
3 CONT On 4 April 1918, Australian units helped the British defend Villers-Bre
3 CONC tonneux. The Germans attacked from the north east forcing the British o
3 CONC ut of the village of Le Hamel. An Australian battalion had to swing bac
3 CONC k to avoid being enveloped but the German advance was stopped by Britis
3 CONC h cavalry working with Australian infantry. In the afternoon, the Austr
3 CONC alians withdrew to the outskirts of Villers-Bretonneux but at the cruci
3 CONC al moment, the Australian 36th Battalion (New South Wales) dashed forwa
3 CONC rd in a spectacular charge. Supported by other British and Australian i
3 CONC nfantry, and later by British cavalry, the 36th threw the Germans back t
3 CONC o old trenches nearly two kilometres from the town, stabilising the lin
3 CONC e.
3 CONT
3 CONT On 24 April, British troops were defending Villers-Bretonneux. The Germ
3 CONC ans attacked at dawn, and with the aid of 13 tanks, which they were usi
3 CONC ng for the first time, they captured the town. A British counter-attack c
3 CONC ommenced at 10 pm the same day led by Australians to the north and sout
3 CONC h. The Australian brigades enveloped Villers-Bretonneux and attempted t
3 CONC o join forces to the east of the town. They were unable to join up in t
3 CONC he dark and many Germans managed to escape. After dawn, the gap was gra
3 CONC dually closed and Australians entered the town from the east and Britis
3 CONC h from the north and west. Villers-Bretonneux was cleared of enemy troo
3 CONC ps on 25 April 1918, the third anniversary of the Anzac landing at Gall
3 CONC ipoli. This action marked the effective end of the German offensive tha
3 CONC t had commenced so successfully more than a month earlier.
3 CONT
3 CONT Communities in Australia helped Villers-Bretonneux to rebuild after the w
3 CONC ar, and the Australian National Memorial to those who fell in the confl
3 CONC ict stands on the Villers-Bretonneux plateau. To this day, the people o
3 CONC f the town annually observe Anzac Day, and the school in the village be
3 CONC ars the simple message on the playground wall “Never forget Australia”.
2 DATE BET 20 APR 1918 AND 28 APR 1918
2 PLAC Villers-Bretonneux, France
