4 CONT A Patrol, consisting of 2 Lt P.G. McCubbin and other ranks left our lin
4 CONC es at 2am 23rd inst to reconnoitre the right of our front. One Rifleman
4 CONC , wounded, reported at Battalion Headquarters at about 3am that 2nd Lt. M
4 CONC cCubbin had been wounded, also some members of the Patrol. Another Patr
4 CONC ol was immediately sent out, no trace the first patrol, which seems to h
4 CONC ave walked into an enemy post, could be found. 2 unwounded members of t
4 CONC he first patrol eventually returned to our lines. 2nd Lt. McCubbin was “
4 CONC Missing”.
4 CONT 2nd Lt. J. Farrell joined for duty.
4 CONT Reports received that enemy would attach at dawn obtained from prisoner
4 CONC s captured on the right of our sector. No attack developed, probably ow
4 CONC ing to wet morning. A quiet day. Work done improving our line and wirin
4 CONC g posts continued. A new MG post made in our line near Battalion Headqu
4 CONC arters. Some enemy gas shells at night.
4 CONT Reports again received late that enemy would attack at dawn on 24th. En
4 CONC emy observed working in VILLIERS BRETINNEUX – WARFUSEE Road, fired on b
4 CONC y our Lewis guns and rifles from our line. Reported to Division by Brig
4 CONC ade Major.
4 CONT Heavy enemy barrage came down at 3.45am. This continues until about 7am
4 CONC , when it became less intense, and chiefly covered ground between Reser
4 CONC ve line and Battalion Headquarters. Barrage included a large proportion o
4 CONC f Gas Shells.
4 CONT Continual reports received from Os.C. Companies that barrage was not on F
4 CONC ront Line or Close support Companies during the above hours. During the n
4 CONC ight 23/24th ½ D Company had been moved into close support on the right a
4 CONC nd half on the left by order of G.O.C. 25th Infantry Brigade. The morni
4 CONC ng was very misty and the enemy put down a heavy smoke barrage at dawn, m
4 CONC aking it impossible to see for more than 20 yards. About 7am a runner f
4 CONC orm “A” Company reported at Battalion Headquarters that the enemy had g
4 CONC ot round the right flank of the company, and was attacking them and the s
4 CONC upport platoons of “D” Company from flank and rear, and was moving towa
4 CONC rds “C” Company.
4 CONT At 8am “B” Company was ordered to form a defensive flank, joining with s
4 CONC upport platoons of “D” company and remains of “C” Company, from “B” Com
4 CONC pany’s right to reserve line. Battalion HQ details moved forward to con
4 CONC tinue the line covering Battn. Headquarters and in touch with 2nd R. Be
4 CONC rkshire Regt. on the right, N.W. of VILLIERS-BRETONNEUX. 2nd Lt. Gurrie
4 CONC r and elements of A C & D Coys joined theis line during the morning.
4 CONT At 9am enemy Very Lights were seen going up on N.W. outskirts of VILLIE
4 CONC RS-BRETONNEUX and enemy machine guns opened fire on vicinity of Bn. Hea
4 CONC dquarters.
4 CONT Reserve line and vicinity of new line joining with 2nd Royal Berkshire R
4 CONC egt. was shelled at intervals all day. B Company on the left was subjec
4 CONC ted to heavy trench Mortar fire at intervals, the enemy advanced severa
4 CONC l times on the right of this company, but each time driven off by rifle a
4 CONC nd machine gun fire.
4 CONT It was afterwards ascertained that the enemy, after breaking through SO
4 CONC UTH of VILLIERRS BRETONNEUX – WARFUSEE Road, had turned in Northwards, b
4 CONC etween our front line and support lines and also in rear of the latter, b
4 CONC eing unobserved owing to the dense mist and smoke barrage. A & C Compan
4 CONC ies taken unawares in the rear were overwhelmed after a sharp fight by s
4 CONC uperior numbers of the enemy, the whole of the two Companies with few e
4 CONC xceptions being killed or captured. Very little was ascertained as to t
4 CONC heir exact fate, but it is known that one Platoon of D Coy. fought to t
4 CONC heir last man, as was completely wiped out. 2nd Lt. Doyle, was dangerou
4 CONC sly wounded while commanding this Platoon, was found on the night of th
4 CONC e 24/25th during the counter-attack by the Australians. The remainder o
4 CONC f the day passed without further attacks on our front , with the except
4 CONC ion of half-hearted attempts to turn the right flank of B Company which w
4 CONC ere frustrated by the effective fire , brought to bear on them by this c
4 CONC ompany.
4 CONT On the night of 24/25th a counter-attack on VILLIERS BRETONNEUX and gro
4 CONC und SW of the village, was carried out by a Australian Brigade, which s
4 CONC urrounded the village, establishing itself on the Eastern outskirts as f
4 CONC ar as the Old Hangars on the VILLIERS BRETONNEUX WARFUSEE road, with it
4 CONC s right flank thrown back. Its left covered the Northern and North West
4 CONC ern parts of the village, and was extended to eth right flank of our B C
4 CONC ompany, where this Company bent back, forming our defensive flank. The A
4 CONC ustralians left at this time was not in touch with B Company’s right, b
4 CONC ut the gap was covered by the continuation of our line joining up with t
4 CONC he 2nd Royal Berkshire Regt. Our lines were shelled at intervals throug
4 CONC hout the night.
