1 EVEN POW Camp at Cassel, France, West of Ypres
2 TYPE military service
2 _SENT  The Battle
3 CONT The German artillery opened fire at 0200 hours on 27
3 CONT May. The preliminary preparation was Bruchmüller’s
3 CONT masterpiece: the Allies were caught almost completely
3 CONT by surprise.5
3 CONT  All firing was done using the calculations
3 CONT of the new Pulkowski Method, which used weather and
3 CONT other ballistic factors to compute registration corrections,
3 CONT rather than determining such corrections by firing,
3 CONT which would have compromised surprise. Although the
3 CONT preparation lasted a mere two hours and 40 minutes,
3 CONT the German gunners hardly missed a forward position,
3 CONT communications trench, command post, or Allied battery.
3 CONT The fire effect was especially devastating because
3 CONT Duchêne had ignored Pétain’s orders to adopt a defence in-depth with a t
3 CONC hinly held front line. The Sixth Army
3 CONT commander-in-chief also unwisely rejected the strong
3 CONT recommendations of his British divisional commanders,
3 CONT who had recent first-hand experience of a Bruchmüller
3 CONT bombardment, dismissing his Allied subordinates with a
3 CONT curt ‘J’ai dit’. Refusing to yield an inch of sacred French soil
3 CONT without a fight, Duchêne packed his forces into the front
3 CONT lines, where they became easy targets for Bruchmüller’s
3 CONT guns. The German artillery fired three million rounds on
3 CONT the first day of Operation BLÜCHER, 50 per cent of which
3 CONT were gas projectiles.
3 CONT Crossing the line of departure at 0440 hours, 20 minutes
3 CONT before first light, the German infantry advanced, preceded
3 CONT by a double creeping barrage. Attacking up hill from the
3 CONT northern base of the Chemin des Dames, they secured
3 CONT the eastern end of the ridge by 0630 hours. Less than
3 CONT four hours later the lead German units crossed the river
3 CONT Aisne, five kilometres miles south of crest of the Chemin
3 CONT des Dames. Using the infiltration tactics they had used
3 CONT with such effect during MICHAEL and GEORGETTE, the
3 CONT advancing Landser moved so fast that the French and
3 CONT British could not withdraw their artillery from the north
3 CONT side of the Aisne. The attackers captured some 45,000
3 CONT prisoners and 650 guns as they surged forward. The Allies
3 CONT also failed to blow the bridges over the Aisne, further
3 CONT facilitating the German advance.
3 CONT By the end of 27 May the German lead elements reached
3 CONT and then crossed the river Vesle, advancing a total of
3 CONT 21 kilometres exceeding the objective for the entire
3 CONT operation. It was the largest single-day advance on the
3 CONT Western Front during the First World War. By the evening
3 CONT of 28 May the German penetration was 24 kilometres
3 CONT deep and 67 kilometres wide at its base. But although
3 CONT Ludendorff had reached his geographic objective far more
3 CONT quickly than he had planned, there were no indicators yet
3 CONT that any significant numbers of the French reserve units
3 CONT were starting to move out of Flanders. Ludendorff had to
3 CONT make a decision: as he had done previously in MICHAEL and
3 CONT GEORGETTE, he completely abandoned the original plan
3 CONT and opportunistically attempted to exploit local tactical
3 CONT success. Without clearly identifying new operational
3 CONT objectives, he ordered the Seventh Army to continue
3 CONT pushing south. In support, he started committing and
3 CONT redeploying from Flanders some of the precious assault
3 CONT divisions he had been husbanding for HAGEN.
2 DATE 27 MAY 1918
2 PLAC Juvincourt, France
2 NOTE Albert was captured on day one of the third Battle of Ansie,
