1 NOTE Royal Artillary  1940 1945
2 CONT Burma Chittagong
2 CONT Private.
2 CONT
2 CONT
2 CONT
2 CONT 04/04/2024 - Further research is being done via a research page for Bur
2 CONC ma on Facebook
2 CONT
2 CONT Details gained from ChatGPT :-
2 CONT
2 CONT British <b>Heavy Artillery Corps</b> in the Burma Campaign is a fascina
2 CONC ting angle, especially because the terrain and climate made traditional h
2 CONC eavy artillery usage challenging. But they <i>were</i> there, and they p
2 CONC layed some key roles, especially in the later phases of the war when lo
2 CONC gistics lines improved.<b>Here's what I can tell you about British Heav
2 CONC y Artillery in Burma (1940–1945):</b><b>🔹 Role and Deployment</b>
2 CONT •
2 CONT Early in the campaign, there was <i>limited use</i> of heavy artillery d
2 CONC ue to the dense jungle, poor roads, and monsoon conditions.
2 CONT •
2 CONT As the campaign evolved (especially from 1943–1945), heavier guns were b
2 CONC rought in to support major offensives like <b>Imphal</b>, <b>Kohima</b>
2 CONC , and the <b>drive to Rangoon</b>.
2 CONT •
2 CONT Artillery was used extensively in <b>defensive fire support</b>, <b>bun
2 CONC ker-busting</b>, and in coordinated <b>creeping barrages</b> with infan
2 CONC try advances.<b>🔹 Units Involved</b>
2 CONT •
2 CONT <b>Royal Artillery (RA)</b> had multiple heavy and medium artillery reg
2 CONC iments attached to the <b>British Fourteenth Army</b> under General Sli
2 CONC m.
2 CONT •
2 CONT Units were often rotated and included:
2 CONT o
2 CONT <b>Medium Regiments</b>: Typically equipped with 5.5-inch guns.
2 CONT o
2 CONT <b>Heavy Regiments</b>: Often had 7.2-inch howitzers or older 60-pounde
2 CONC r guns.
2 CONT •
2 CONT Artillery support was coordinated under divisional and corps artillery c
2 CONC ommands (e.g., XXXIII Corps, IV Corps).<b>🔹 Equipment Used</b>
2 CONT •
2 CONT <b>5.5-inch Gun (BL)</b> – Workhorse of medium artillery.
2 CONT •
2 CONT <b>7.2-inch Howitzer</b> – Used in heavy regiments; good for deep bomba
2 CONC rdment.
2 CONT •
2 CONT <b>25-pounder field guns</b> were also widely used, but technically not i
2 CONC n the “heavy” class—they were the backbone of artillery across all fron
2 CONC ts.<b>🔹 Notable Actions</b>
2 CONT •
2 CONT <b>Battle of Imphal (1944)</b> – Artillery was used effectively in defe
2 CONC nsive roles, repelling Japanese assaults.
2 CONT •
2 CONT <b>Kohima Ridge</b> – Artillery fire played a major role in halting the J
2 CONC apanese advance.
2 CONT •
2 CONT During the <b>advance on Meiktila and Mandalay</b>, coordinated barrage
2 CONC s were essential in breaking Japanese defenses.<b>🔹 Challenges</b>
2 CONT •
2 CONT <b>Transporting heavy guns</b> through jungle and mountainous terrain r
2 CONC equired ingenuity—elephants, bulldozers, and even airlifting in parts.
2 CONT •
2 CONT Monsoons turned roads into rivers, limiting mobility and ammo resupply.
2 CONT
2 CONT
2 CONT
