3 CONC 1838)</b>
3 CONT <b>Departure</b>: 10 April 1838
3 CONT <b>Arrival</b>: 25 August 1838
3 CONT <b>Duration</b>: Approximately <b>135 days</b> at sea (about 4.5 months
3 CONC )<b>⚓ 1. The Ship & Its Purpose</b>
3 CONT The <i>Lord William Bentinck</i> was one of many <b>convict transport s
3 CONC hips</b> contracted by the British government. It was outfitted specifi
3 CONC cally to move prisoners from England to penal colonies — in this case, <
3 CONC b>Van Diemen’s Land</b>, the most remote and feared of them all.
3 CONT •
3 CONT The ship would have held <b>150–300 male convicts</b>, guarded by a mil
3 CONC itary detachment and overseen by a ship's surgeon and captain.
3 CONT •
3 CONT Simon would have been shackled when boarding, but restraints were often r
3 CONC emoved at sea for health reasons.<b>🛏️ 2. Conditions on Board</b>
3 CONT Although conditions had <b>improved slightly by the late 1830s</b>, the
3 CONC y were still grim by any modern standard:
3 CONT •
3 CONT <b>Sleeping</b>: Hammocks or wooden bunks, often in dark, poorly ventil
3 CONC ated below-deck holds.
3 CONT •
3 CONT <b>Space</b>: Cramped. Each man had a small, shared space, with barely e
3 CONC nough room to sit up.
3 CONT •
3 CONT <b>Food</b>: Salt meat, hard tack, oatmeal, rice, and dried peas. Fresh f
3 CONC ood was rare. Water was rationed.
