3 CONT <b>Health</b>: Although ships had a designated <b>Surgeon Superintenden
3 CONC t</b> to care for prisoners (a reform after earlier death tolls), disea
3 CONC se outbreaks still occurred. Scurvy, typhoid, and fever were frequent.
3 CONT Simon dying <b>less than two years after arrival</b> suggests he may ha
3 CONC ve <b>suffered illness on board</b> or never recovered from the toll it t
3 CONC ook.<b>🧑‍🏫 3. Daily Life & Routine</b>
3 CONT •
3 CONT Prisoners were required to <b>wash, exercise</b>, and sometimes even pa
3 CONC rticipate in <b>morning prayers</b>.
3 CONT •
3 CONT When weather allowed, convicts were brought on deck for air.
3 CONT •
3 CONT Some were <b>assigned tasks</b> (like sewing, cleaning, or reading scri
3 CONC pture).
3 CONT •
3 CONT <b>Literacy programs</b> were introduced on some voyages to "reform" pr
3 CONC isoners — it’s possible Simon had access to basic instruction or religi
3 CONC ous tracts.<b>⚰️ 4. Mortality</b>
3 CONT •
3 CONT Some voyages in the 1830s had <b>no deaths</b>, others had several.
3 CONT •
3 CONT If Simon was already in poor health from <b>poverty, malnutrition</b>, o
3 CONC r <b>disease in prison</b>, the long voyage would have worsened his con
3 CONC dition.
3 CONT •
3 CONT He survived the journey, but <b>died in January 1840</b>, less than two y
3 CONC ears after arrival — suggesting either <b>lingering illness</b>, <b>har
3 CONC sh labour</b>, or further hardship in the colony.<b>📜 5. Historical Pe
3 CONC rspective</b>
3 CONT Although transportation was often presented as a chance for redemption, i
3 CONC n reality, many transported convicts like Simon were <b>poor, unskilled r
3 CONC ural workers</b>, punished harshly for minor crimes in a society stacke
3 CONC d against them.
3 CONT Their transportation was part punishment, part colonial labour strategy — c
3 CONC onvicts built infrastructure, worked farms, or were assigned to settler
3 CONC s. For many, it was effectively <b>a life sentence in exile</b>.
3 CONT If you'd like, I can help you track down the <b>surgeon's voyage report
3 CONC </b> or <b>convict muster rolls</b> from the <i>Lord William Bentinck</
3 CONC i>. These sometimes note <b>illnesses, deaths, or behaviour</b> aboard s
3 CONC pecific voyages — and Simon might be listed.
3 CONT Would you like to explore that next?
