1 NOTE <b>Biography </b>
2 CONT <b>Birth:</b> William D'Oyly <i>[aka Doyley -- born circa,1400]</i> of E
2 CONC weden in Hambleden, county. Buckinghamshire. William was defined as a '
2 CONC gentleman'.
2 CONT <i>[He was nephew and heir of John D'Oyly through 'John's' brother 'Ric
2 CONC hard' , [1] & [2]]</i>
2 CONT <b>Succession: </b>William became 'representative' <i>[the 'patriarchal
2 CONC -descendant']</i> of the family when 'Richard' <i>[his father]</i> died i
2 CONC n 1435 <i>[reference: Extinct and Dormant Baronetcies]</i> [3], and suc
2 CONC ceeded to <i>[what was then-defined as]</i> the family's 'shattered-est
2 CONC ates'.
2 CONT He was resident at East Lydeford lands in 1431, but was representative <
2 CONC i>[patriarch]</i> of the 'Eweden' based family in 1440. - - - Records a
2 CONC re light-on, <i>[maybe due, to the suggested ‘poverty’, lack of 'acclai
2 CONC m', 'honour’s', etc. ]</i>. William seems to have led a 'quiet-agricult
2 CONC ural' life at the family 'manor' of Eweden.
2 CONT <b>Marriage:</b> William did marry a lady named Eleanor ,<i>[reference: T
2 CONC he History of the House of D’Oyly [ref:237] ]</i> [4] but of what famil
2 CONC y-name is unknown.
2 CONT <b>William and Eleanor's children</b> The record indicate there were, t
2 CONC wo son's and three daughters:<b> </b>
2 CONT • John <i>[b.c.1440]</i> . who married Isabella Moore. .
2 CONT • Robert, <i>[of whom nothing has been recorded]</i>.
2 CONT • Isabella, of whom also nothing is known.
2 CONT • Margaret, reputedly married, Robert Knollys, grandson of "Sir Robert K
2 CONC nollys" <i>[through his second son Thomas]</i> of North Mymms, county H
2 CONC ertfordshire, [5] [confirmation - citation] [6]
2 CONT • Alice, of whom nothing is known.
2 CONT <b>Death:</b> It is recorded that William died, under 50 years of age, <
2 CONC i>[post 1449]</i>. He left 'Eleanor' pregnant with child, <i>[his other c
2 CONC hildren, still minors.]</i>.
2 CONT <b>Research:</b> Much of the above text is a ‘contemporary-transcript’ o
2 CONC f that found In the "HISTORY OF THE HOUSE OF D'OYLY". <i>[By: Wm. D'Oyl
2 CONC y Bayley]</i>. Per the chapters: D'OYLY’s of EWEDEN and GREENLAND, co. <
2 CONC i>[Buckinghamshire]</i> and finally, of CHISLEHAMPTON, co. <i>[Oxfordsh
2 CONC ire]</i> , BARONET. A. D. 1131 to 1773. [2]<b>Sources </b>
2 CONT 1. ↑ British History Online [anchor-ref:46] (https://www.british-histor
2 CONC y.ac.uk/vch/oxon/vol8/pp131-138#anchorn46)
2 CONT 2. ↑ 2.0 2.1 History of the House of D’Oyly [ref:236] [ https://web.arc
2 CONC hive.org/web/20130719071650/http:/www.watkinsweb.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk/#
2 CONC _ftnref236]
2 CONT 3. ↑ Burke, John. <i>A Genealogical and Heraldic History of the Extinct a
2 CONC nd Dormant Baronetcies of England, Ireland, and Scotland,</i> Second Ed
2 CONC . (Scott, Webster, and Geary, London, 1841) "D'Oyley, of Chiselhampton,
2 CONC " [ https://books.google.com/books?id=DqkTAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA165 ref: page.1
2 CONC 65 ].
2 CONT 4. ↑ History of the House of D’Oyly [ref:237] ( https://web.archive.org
2 CONC /web/20130719071650/http:/www.watkinsweb.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk/#_ftnref2
