1 NOTE <b>Biography </b>Bernard Brocas was born about 1354, son and heir of Be
2 CONC rnard Brocas and his first wife, Agnes Vavasour. However the Visitation o
2 CONC f Hampshire gives his mother as Bernard's second wife, Mary de Roches  w
2 CONC hich is followed by Royal Berkshire Histories.
2 CONT He was attainted in the first year of the reign of Henry IV.
2 CONT He was executed on the 28th of January 1400. His heir was his son Willi
2 CONC am.
2 CONT <b>Sources </b>
2 CONT 1. ↑ 1.0 1.1 M. C. B. Dawes, H. C. Johnson, M. M. Condon, C. A. Cook an
2 CONC d H. E. Jones, 'Inquisitions Post Mortem, Richard II, File 86', in Cale
2 CONC ndar of Inquisitions Post Mortem, Volume 17, Richard II (London, 1988), p
2 CONC p. 232-240. British History Online http://www.british-history.ac.uk/inq
2 CONC uis-post-mortem/vol17/pp232-240 [accessed 6 December 2020].
2 CONT 2. ↑ 2.0 2.1 Pedigrees from the visitation of Hampshire made by Thomas B
2 CONC enolt, Clarenceulx a 1530 : enlarged with the vissitation of the same c
2 CONC ounty made by Robert Cooke, Clarenceulx anno 1575 both which are contin
2 CONC ued with the vissitation made by John Phillipott, Somersett (for Willia
2 CONC m Camden, Clarenceux) in a 1622 most part then done & finished in a 163
2 CONC 4. As collected by Richard Mundy in Harleian ms. no. 1544 by Benolt, Th
2 CONC omas, d. 1534; Cooke, Robert, d. 1592; Philipot, John, 1589?-1645; Mund
2 CONC y, Richard; Rylands, W. Harry (William Harry), 1847-1922 Page 130: Broc
2 CONC as
2 CONT 3. ↑ David Nash Ford's Royal Berkshire History: Sir Bernard Brocas
2 CONT 4. ↑ 4.0 4.1 J. L. Kirby, 'Inquisitions Post Mortem, Henry IV, Entries 1
2 CONC -50', in Calendar of Inquisitions Post Mortem: Volume 18, Henry IV (Lon
2 CONC don, 1987), pp. 1-20. British History Online http://www.british-history
2 CONC .ac.uk/inquis-post-mortem/vol18/pp1-20 [accessed 6 December 2020].
