1 BIRT
2 DATE 1354
2 PLAC Hampshire, England
2 NOTE <b>Sir Bernard Brocas</b> (c. 1354 – 5 February 1400) was an English kn
3 CONC ight, landowner and administrator who was executed for his part in the E
3 CONC piphany Rising.[1]<b>Life</b>
3 CONT Born about 1354 as the eldest son of Sir Bernard Brocas (1330–1395) of C
3 CONC lewer in Berkshire and his first wife Agnes Vavasour, his father was a c
3 CONC lose friend of Edward, the Black Prince. He would therefore have been a
3 CONC cquainted as a child with the Black Prince's son, the future king Richa
3 CONC rd II. Inheriting most of his mother's estates, he became an esquire by 1
3 CONC 385 and by 1390 was a knight in the King's service.[2]
3 CONT In 1395 he inherited his father's estates but remained living at Beaure
3 CONC paire. He also inherited the hereditary office of Master of the Buckhou
3 CONC nds. He seems to have acted as a feoffee for William Scrope, Earl of Wi
3 CONC ltshire, one of Richard's principal ministers. He may not have been ass
3 CONC iduous in attending court however, as surviving documents record him mo
3 CONC st often in Hampshire, where he was appointed a JP in 1396.[2]
3 CONT In 1400, after Richard II had been deposed by Henry IV, he joined in a c
3 CONC onspiracy known as the Epiphany Rising to kill Henry and restore Richar
3 CONC d to the throne. The plot was foiled when details were leaked and the c
3 CONC onspirators were chased westwards from Windsor Castle by an armed force
3 CONC . Brocas was captured in Cirencester and sent to the Tower of London, w
3 CONC here he was tried for treason, with three others, by Thomas FitzAlan, 1
3 CONC 2th Earl of Arundel and on 4 February condemned to death. The following d
3 CONC ay he was forced to walk to Tyburn and was there executed, presumably b
3 CONC y beheading. He was buried in the Franciscan church of Greyfriars, Lond
3 CONC on.[2]<b>Family</b>
3 CONT Some time before 1380 he married Joan (died 1429), who was the daughter o
3 CONC f either Sir Thomas Midelton or Gilbert Banbury of Holybourne. They liv
3 CONC ed at Beaurepaire in the parish of Sherborne St John in Hampshire and h
3 CONC ad six children, including
3 CONT • the elder son William Brocas (c. 1379–1456), MP for Hampshire and Hig
3 CONC h Sheriff of Hampshire
3 CONT • a younger son Bernard Brocas (died c. 1431), MP for Hampshire
3 CONT • the eldest daughter Catherine Brocas, who married Sir Robert Delamare o
3 CONC f Aldermaston
3 CONT Although a convicted traitor's goods and lands were forfeit to the Crow
3 CONC n, Henry IV was not vindictive to the family. Ten days after the execut
3 CONC ion, he let the widow Joan have her husband's goods and later that year t
3 CONC he lands yielding an annual income of 300 pounds were granted to the el
3 CONC der son William.[2]
3 CONT The executors of the will of Bernard Brocas, knight, were: Mathew de Gu
3 CONC rney, John Chitterne, John Marnham, John Bridbrok, and Theobald Wykham.
3 CONC [3]
