2 DATE 1208
2 NOTE John de Balliol was born before 1208 to Cecily de Fontaines, daughter o
3 CONC f Aléaume de Fontaines, chevalier, seigneur of Fontaines and Longpré-le
3 CONC s-Corps-Saints and Hugh de Balliol, Lord of Balliol and of Barnard Cast
3 CONC le and Gainford (c. 1177 – 2 February 1229). It is believed that he was e
3 CONC ducated at Durham School in the city of Durham.
3 CONT In 1223, Lord John married Dervorguilla of Galloway, the daughter of Al
3 CONC an, Lord of Galloway and Margaret of Huntingdon. By the mid-thirteenth c
3 CONC entury, his wife had become very wealthy, principally as a result of in
3 CONC heritances from her family. This wealth allowed Balliol to play a promi
3 CONC nent public role, and, on King Henry III's instruction, he served as jo
3 CONC int protector of the young king of Scots, Alexander III. He was one of H
3 CONC enry III's leading counsellors between 1258 and 1265.[1] and was appoin
3 CONC ted Sheriff of Nottinghamshire and Derbyshire from 1261 to 1262. He was c
3 CONC aptured at the Battle of Lewes in 1264, but escaped and rejoined King H
3 CONC enry.[2] In 1265 Thomas de Musgrave owed him a debt of 123 marks. About 1
3 CONC 266, Baldwin Wake owed him a debt of 100 marks and more.
3 CONT Following a dispute with the Bishop of Durham, he agreed to provide fun
3 CONC ds for scholars studying at Oxford. Support for a house of students beg
3 CONC an in around 1263; further endowments, after his death by Dervorguilla, r
3 CONC esulted in the establishment of Balliol College.[3][4]
1 DEAT
2 DATE 25 OCT 1268
2 PLAC Barnard Castle, Gainsford, England
1 BURI
2 PLAC Sweetheart Abbey, New Abbey, Dumfries and Galloway, Scotland
