1 NAME Devorguilla /Of Galloway/
2 GIVN Devorguilla
2 SURN Of Galloway
1 SEX F
1 _UID FA825C0991224508862D0A41C23CE0722FD1
1 CHAN
2 DATE 6 OCT 2023
1 _COLOR 4
1 BIRT
2 DATE 1210
2 PLAC Wigtownshire, Scotland
1 DEAT
2 DATE 28 JAN 1290
2 PLAC Bedfordshire, England
1 BURI
2 DATE 31 JAN 1290
2 PLAC New Abbey, Dumfries and Galloway, Scotland
1 EVEN Life
2 TYPE Misc
2 _SENT The Balliol family into which Dervorguilla married was based at Barnard C
3 CONC astle in County Durham, England. Although the date of her birth is unce
3 CONC rtain, her apparent age of 13 was by no means unusually early for betro
3 CONC thal and marriage at the time.
3 CONT
3 CONT In 1263, her husband Sir John was required to make penance after a land d
3 CONC ispute with Walter of Kirkham, Bishop of Durham. Part of this took the v
3 CONC ery expensive form of founding a College for the poor at the University o
3 CONC f Oxford. Sir John's own finances were less substantial than those of h
3 CONC is wife, however, and long after his death it fell to Dervorguilla to c
3 CONC onfirm the foundation, with the blessing of the same Bishop as well as t
3 CONC he University hierarchy. She established a permanent endowment for the C
3 CONC ollege in 1282, as well as its first formal Statutes. The college still r
3 CONC etains the name Balliol College, where the history students' society is c
3 CONC alled the Dervorguilla Society and an annual seminar series featuring w
3 CONC omen in academia is called the Dervorguilla Seminar Series. While a Req
3 CONC uiem Mass in Latin was sung at Balliol for the 700th anniversary of her d
3 CONC eath, it is believed that this was sung as a one-off, rather than havin
3 CONC g been marked in previous centuries.
3 CONT
3 CONT Dervorguilla founded a Cistercian Abbey 7 miles south of Dumfries and G
3 CONC alloway Scotland, in April 1273. It still stands as a picturesque ruin o
3 CONC f red sandstone. It is claimed that she was also responsible for the es
3 CONC tablishment of the first library in Dundee.[1]
3 CONT
3 CONT
3 CONT Devorguilla Bridge, Dumfries
3 CONT When Sir John died in 1269, Dervorguilla had his heart embalmed and kep
3 CONC t in a casket of ivory bound with silver. The casket travelled with her f
3 CONC or the rest of her life. In 1274–5 John de Folkesworth arraigned an ass
3 CONC ize of novel disseisin against Dervorguilla and others touching a tenem
3 CONC ent in Stibbington, Northamptonshire. In 1275–6 Robert de Ferrers arrai
3 CONC gned an assize of mort d'ancestor against her touching a messuage in Re
3 CONC pton, Derbyshire. In 1280 Sir John de Balliol's executors, including De
3 CONC rvorguilla, sued Alan Fitz Count regarding a debt of £100 claimed by th
3 CONC e executors from Alan. In 1280 she was granted letters of attorney to T
3 CONC homas de Hunsingore and another in England, she staying in Galloway. Th
3 CONC e same year Dervorguilla, Margaret de Ferrers, Countess of Derby, Ellen
3 CONC , widow of Alan la Zouche, and Alexander Comyn, Earl of Buchan, and Eli
3 CONC zabeth his wife sued Roger de Clifford and Isabel his wife and Roger de L
3 CONC eybourne and Idoine his wife regarding the manors of Wyntone, King’s Me
3 CONC aburn, Appleby, and Brough-under-Stainmore, and a moiety of the manor o
3 CONC f Kirkby Stephen, all in Westmorland. The same year Dervorguilla sued J
3 CONC ohn de Veer for a debt of £24. In 1280–1 Laurence Duket arraigned an as
3 CONC size of novel disseisin again Dervorguilla and others touching a hedge d
3 CONC estroyed in Cotingham, Middlesex. In 1288 she reached agreement with Jo
3 CONC hn, Abbot of Ramsey, regarding a fishery in Ellington.
3 CONT
3 CONT In her last years, the main line of the Royal House of Scotland was thr
3 CONC eatened by a lack of male heirs, and Dervorguilla, who died just before t
3 CONC he young heiress Margaret, the Maid of Norway, might, if she had outliv
3 CONC ed her, have been one of the claimants to her throne. Dervorguilla was b
3 CONC uried beside her husband at New Abbey, which was christened 'Sweetheart A
3 CONC bbey', the name which it retains to this day. The depredations suffered b
3 CONC y the Abbey in subsequent periods have caused both graves to be lost. A r
3 CONC eplica is to be found in the covered south transept.
