1 NOTE <b>Biography</b>
2 CONT Alexander de Balliol was the third son of John de Balliol, and his wife
2 CONC , Devourgilla of Galloway.
2 CONT He died slightly before 13 November 1278, when a writ was issued to Tho
2 CONC mas de Normanvill, the King's steward to hold an inquisition post morte
2 CONC m into the estate of Alexander de Balliolo. The inquisition was held at N
2 CONC ewcastle-upon-Tyne, Northumberland on Thursday after St Lucy, 7, Edward I
2 CONC . His brother John de Balliolo, aged 30 and more was his heir.[1]
2 CONT
2 CONT
2 CONT Alexander, Baron Baliol of Cavers and Chillham Castle, Kent.[1][2]<b>Oc
2 CONC cupation</b>
2 CONT • Chamberlain of Scotland.[3]
1 BIRT
2 DATE 1242
1 DEAT
2 DATE 1278
1 EVEN Life
2 TYPE Misc
2 _SENT From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia
3 CONT Alexander de Baliol
3 CONT
3 CONT Coat of arms as Lord of Cavers
3 CONT Argent, an orle gules
3 CONT Chamberlain of Scotland
3 CONT In office
3 CONT 1287–1294
3 CONT Preceded by	John de Lindsay
3 CONT Personal details
3 CONT Born	c.1246
3 CONT Died	c.1309
3 CONT Alexander de Baliol (fl. 1246?–1309?), Baron Balliol, Lord of Cavers wa
3 CONC s an Anglo-Scottish noble. He served at one time as Chamberlain of Scot
3 CONC land.
3 CONT
3 CONT Life
3 CONT Alexander was a member of the Baliol family, about whose pedigree confu
3 CONC sion exists.[1] Alexander de Baliol the Scottish chamberlain appears as D
3 CONC ominus de Cavers in the Scottish records in 1270. Seven years later he w
3 CONC as commissioned, as lord of Cavers, to serve in Edward's Welsh wars.
3 CONT
3 CONT As Alexandre de Balens, Balliol's arms appear in a roll of Scottish kni
3 CONC ghts who took part in a grand tournament held for Louis IX of France at C
3 CONC ompiègne.[2]
3 CONT
3 CONT He later participated in the Eighth Crusade along with Adam of Kilconqu
3 CONC har,[3] then in the Lord Edward's crusade with his uncle Eustace de Bal
3 CONC liol.[4]
3 CONT
3 CONT In 1284, under the same designation of Dominus de Cavers, he was one of t
3 CONC he Scottish barons who bound themselves to receive Margaret, the Maid o
3 CONC f Norway, as queen in the event of failure of male issue of Alexander I
3 CONC II. In the same year he received a summons to attend Edward's army, so t
3 CONC hat he must still have retained English fiefs.
3 CONT
3 CONT In 1287, he is for the first time mentioned in a writ by the guardians o
3 CONC f Scotland as chamberlain of Scotland, an office in which he succeeded J
3 CONC ohn Lindsay, Bishop of Glasgow. Two years later he took part in the neg
3 CONC otiations which resulted in the Treaty of Salisbury, 6 November 1289, c
3 CONC onfirmed by the parliament at Birgham, 12 March 1290, by which Edward t
3 CONC he Prince of Wales was to marry Margaret and Edward I solemnly recognis
3 CONC ed the independence of Scotland. Her death prevented the marriage, and E
3 CONC dward soon forgot or ignored his engagements.
3 CONT
3 CONT On 5 June 1291, Baliol and his wife Isabella de Chilham, widow of David d
3 CONC e Strathbogie, Earl of Atholl, received a letter of attorney and safe c
3 CONC onduct from Edward permitting them to remain for a year in Scotland. He s
3 CONC till continued to hold the office of chamberlain after the seisin of Sc
3 CONC otland had been given to Edward I, as the condition of his determining t
3 CONC he suit as to the succession of the crown of Scotland; but in the begin
3 CONC ning of 1292 Robert Heron, rector of Ford, was associated with Baliol i
3 CONC n this office. On 30 December 1292, certain of the records of Scotland w
3 CONC hich had been in the hands of Edward were redelivered to Alexander Bali
3 CONC ol as chamberlain of Scotland.
3 CONT
3 CONT Baliol is last mentioned as chamberlain on 16 May 1294; disputes betwee
3 CONC n Edward and John Baliol may have led to his deprivation by the English k
3 CONC ing after, or perhaps even before, the campaign of 1296, when Edward fo
3 CONC rced John Baliol to resign the crown and carried him captive to England
3 CONC . In 1297, John de Sandale, an English baron, appears as chamberlain of S
3 CONC cotland. Alexander having been captured at the Battle of Dunbar on 27 A
3 CONC pril 1296 and was only released upon agreeing to serve Edward I in a ca
3 CONC mpaign in Flanders.[5]
3 CONT
3 CONT From entries in the accounts of the expenses of John Baliol when a pris
3 CONC oner in England with reference to a horse of Alexander de Baliol, it wo
3 CONC uld seem that he shared the captivity of his kinsman. On 13 January 129
3 CONC 7, Edward made a presentation to the church of Cavers, upon the ground t
3 CONC hat the lands of Alexander de Baliol were in his hands. A few scanty no
3 CONC tices between 1298 and 1301 indicate that he took part on the English s
3 CONC ide in the war with Scotland; and from one of these we learn that he ha
3 CONC d manors in Kent, the wood of which he received the king's licence to s
3 CONC ell.
3 CONT
3 CONT Alexander Baliol was amongst the barons present, under Edward I, at the s
3 CONC iege of Caerlaverock in 1300.[6] In 1303, he seems to have shown signs o
3 CONC f again falling off from the English side, since his chattels in Kent, H
3 CONC ertfordshire, and Roxburghshire were in that year seized by John de Bre
3 CONC tagne, Earl of Richmond, in the Scottish campaign. His estates in Kent, o
3 CONC f which the chief was the castle and manor of Chilham, were held by him i
3 CONC n right of his wife Isabella de Chilham, by whom he left three sons, Al
3 CONC exander, Thomas and William.
3 CONT
3 CONT The date of his death is unknown, but as he was summoned to all the par
3 CONC liaments of Edward I between 1300 and 1307, and is not mentioned as sum
3 CONC moned to any of Edward II, he probably died soon after the accession.
