2 NAME Descendents of William the Conqueror
2 URL www.william.1.co.uk/w1.html
1 BIRT
2 DATE 1028
2 PLAC Falaise, Normandy, France
1 EVEN
2 TYPE Misc
2 _SENT William I[a] (c. 1028[1] – 9 September 1087), usually known as William t
3 CONC he Conqueror and sometimes William the Bastard,[2][b] was the first Nor
3 CONC man king of England, reigning from 1066 until his death in 1087. A desc
3 CONC endant of Rollo, he was Duke of Normandy from 1035 onward. By 1060, fol
3 CONC lowing a long struggle to establish his throne, his hold on Normandy wa
3 CONC s secure. In 1066, following the death of Edward the Confessor, William i
3 CONC nvaded England, leading an army of Normans to victory over the Anglo-Sa
3 CONC xon forces of Harold Godwinson at the Battle of Hastings, and suppresse
3 CONC d subsequent English revolts in what has become known as the Norman Con
3 CONC quest. The rest of his life was marked by struggles to consolidate his h
3 CONC old over England and his continental lands, and by difficulties with hi
3 CONC s eldest son, Robert Curthose.
3 CONT
3 CONT William was the son of the unmarried Duke Robert I of Normandy and his m
3 CONC istress Herleva. His illegitimate status and his youth caused some diff
3 CONC iculties for him after he succeeded his father, as did the anarchy whic
3 CONC h plagued the first years of his rule. During his childhood and adolesc
3 CONC ence, members of the Norman aristocracy battled each other, both for co
3 CONC ntrol of the child duke, and for their own ends. In 1047, William was a
3 CONC ble to quash a rebellion and begin to establish his authority over the d
3 CONC uchy, a process that was not complete until about 1060. His marriage in t
3 CONC he 1050s to Matilda of Flanders provided him with a powerful ally in th
3 CONC e neighbouring county of Flanders. By the time of his marriage, William w
3 CONC as able to arrange the appointment of his supporters as bishops and abb
3 CONC ots in the Norman church. His consolidation of power allowed him to exp
3 CONC and his horizons, and he secured control of the neighbouring county of M
3 CONC aine by 1062.
3 CONT
3 CONT In the 1050s and early 1060s, William became a contender for the throne o
3 CONC f England held by the childless Edward the Confessor, his first cousin o
3 CONC nce removed. There were other potential claimants, including the powerf
3 CONC ul English earl Harold Godwinson, whom Edward named as king on his deat
3 CONC hbed in January 1066. Arguing that Edward had previously promised the t
3 CONC hrone to him and that Harold had sworn to support his claim, William bu
3 CONC ilt a large fleet and invaded England in September 1066. He decisively d
3 CONC efeated and killed Harold at the Battle of Hastings on 14 October 1066. A
3 CONC fter further military efforts, William was crowned king on Christmas Da
3 CONC y, 1066, in London. He made arrangements for the governance of England i
3 CONC n early 1067 before returning to Normandy. Several unsuccessful rebelli
3 CONC ons followed, but William's hold was mostly secure on England by 1075, a
3 CONC llowing him to spend the greater part of his reign in continental Europ
3 CONC e.
3 CONT
3 CONT William's final years were marked by difficulties in his continental do
3 CONC mains, troubles with his son, Robert, and threatened invasions of Engla
3 CONC nd by the Danes. In 1086, he ordered the compilation of the Domesday Bo
3 CONC ok, a survey listing all of the land-holdings in England along with the
3 CONC ir pre-Conquest and current holders. He died in September 1087 while le
3 CONC ading a campaign in northern France, and was buried in Caen. His reign i
3 CONC n England was marked by the construction of castles, settling a new Nor
3 CONC man nobility on the land, and change in the composition of the English c
3 CONC lergy. He did not try to integrate his domains into one empire but cont
3 CONC inued to administer each part separately. His lands were divided after h
3 CONC is death: Normandy went to Robert, and England went to his second survi
3 CONC ving son, William Rufus.
3 CONT
3 CONT Background
3 CONT Norsemen first began raiding in what became Normandy in the late 8th ce
3 CONC ntury. Permanent Scandinavian settlement occurred before 911, when Roll
3 CONC o, one of the Viking leaders, and King Charles the Simple of France rea
3 CONC ched an agreement ceding the county of Rouen to Rollo. The lands around R
3 CONC ouen became the core of the later duchy of Normandy.[3] Normandy may ha
3 CONC ve been used as a base when Scandinavian attacks on England were renewe
3 CONC d at the end of the 10th century, which would have worsened relations b
3 CONC etween England and Normandy.[4] In an effort to improve matters, King Æ
3 CONC thelred the Unready took Emma, sister of Richard II, Duke of Normandy, a
3 CONC s his second wife in 1002.[5]
3 CONT
3 CONT Danish raids on England continued, and Æthelred sought help from Richar
3 CONC d, taking refuge in Normandy in 1013 when King Swein I of Denmark drove Æ
3 CONC thelred and his family from England. Swein's death in 1014 allowed Æthe
3 CONC lred to return home, but Swein's son Cnut contested Æthelred's return. Æ
3 CONC thelred died unexpectedly in 1016, and Cnut became king of England. Æth
3 CONC elred and Emma's two sons, Edward and Alfred, went into exile in Norman
3 CONC dy while their mother, Emma, became Cnut's second wife.[6]
3 CONT
3 CONT After Cnut's death in 1035, the English throne fell to Harold Harefoot, h
3 CONC is son by his first wife, while Harthacnut, his son by Emma, became kin
3 CONC g in Denmark. England remained unstable. Alfred returned to England in 1
3 CONC 036 to visit his mother and perhaps to challenge Harold as king. One st
3 CONC ory implicates Earl Godwin of Wessex in Alfred's subsequent death, but o
3 CONC thers blame Harold. Emma went into exile in Flanders until Harthacnut b
3 CONC ecame king following Harold's death in 1040, and his half-brother Edwar
3 CONC d followed Harthacnut to England; Edward was proclaimed king after Hart
3 CONC hacnut's death in June 1042.[7][c]
3 CONT
3 CONT Early life
3 CONT
3 CONT Château de Falaise in Falaise, Lower Normandy, France; William was born i
3 CONC n an earlier building here.
3 CONT William was born in 1027 or 1028 at Falaise, Duchy of Normandy, most li
3 CONC kely towards the end of 1028.[1][8][d] He was the only son of Robert I, s
3 CONC on of Richard II.[e] His mother Herleva was a daughter of Fulbert of Fa
3 CONC laise; he may have been a tanner or embalmer.[9] Herleva was possibly a m
3 CONC ember of the ducal household, but did not marry Robert.[2] She later ma
3 CONC rried Herluin de Conteville, with whom she had two sons – Odo of Bayeux a
3 CONC nd Count Robert of Mortain – and a daughter whose name is unknown.[f] O
3 CONC ne of Herleva's brothers, Walter, became a supporter and protector of W
3 CONC illiam during his minority.[9][g] Robert I also had a daughter, Adelaid
3 CONC e, by another mistress.[12]
3 CONT
3 CONT Robert I succeeded his elder brother Richard III as duke on 6 August 10
3 CONC 27.[1] The brothers had been at odds over the succession, and Richard's d
3 CONC eath was sudden. Robert was accused by some writers of killing Richard, a p
3 CONC lausible but now unprovable charge.[13] Conditions in Normandy were uns
3 CONC ettled, as noble families despoiled the Church and Alan III of Brittany w
3 CONC aged war against the duchy, possibly in an attempt to take control. By 1
3 CONC 031 Robert had gathered considerable support from noblemen, many of who
3 CONC m would become prominent during William's life. They included the duke'
3 CONC s uncle Robert, the archbishop of Rouen, who had originally opposed the d
3 CONC uke; Osbern, a nephew of Gunnor the wife of Richard I; and Gilbert of B
3 CONC rionne, a grandson of Richard I.[14] After his accession, Robert contin
3 CONC ued Norman support for the English princes Edward and Alfred, who were s
3 CONC till in exile in northern France.[2]
3 CONT
3 CONT There are indications that Robert may have been briefly betrothed to a d
3 CONC aughter of King Cnut, but no marriage took place. It is unclear whether W
3 CONC illiam would have been supplanted in the ducal succession if Robert had h
3 CONC ad a legitimate son. Earlier dukes had been illegitimate, and William's a
3 CONC ssociation with his father on ducal charters appears to indicate that W
3 CONC illiam was considered Robert's most likely heir.[2] In 1034 the duke de
3 CONC cided to go on pilgrimage to Jerusalem. Although some of his supporters t
3 CONC ried to dissuade him from undertaking the journey, he convened a counci
3 CONC l in January 1035 and had the assembled Norman magnates swear fealty to W
3 CONC illiam as his heir[2][15] before leaving for Jerusalem. He died in earl
3 CONC y July at Nicea, on his way back to Normandy.[15]
