2 TYPE Misc
2 _SENT Robert the Devil, also known as 'the Magnificent', Duke of Normandy was t
3 CONC he father of William the Conqueror, the founder of England's dynasty of N
3 CONC orman kings, Robert reigned as Duke of Normandy from 1027 until his dea
3 CONC th.
3 CONT
3 CONT Robert was born on 22 June 1000, the son of Richard II 'the Good' Duke o
3 CONC f Normandy. and Judith, daughter of Conan I, Duke of Brittany and his w
3 CONC ife Ermengarde. Robert became Count of Hiémois on the death of his fath
3 CONC er Duke Richard II in August 1026, his elder brother succeeded as ruler o
3 CONC f Normandy as Duke Richard III. Robert rose in rebellion against his br
3 CONC other the new duke but was defeated and forced to swear fealty to Richa
3 CONC rd.
3 CONT
3 CONT When Richard died the following year, Robert succeeded to the dukedom o
3 CONC f Normandy. It was rumoured that Robert had been poisoned and that his b
3 CONC rother was implicated in his untimely death but there was no proof his i
3 CONC nvolvement. Richard's son, Nicholas, retired to the safety of a monaste
3 CONC ry. Robert is usually referred to as Robert I of Normandy, but sometime
3 CONC s Robert II with his Viking ancestor Rollo 'the Ganger' as Robert I.
3 CONT
3 CONT Soon after his accession as duke, Robert raised an army against his unc
3 CONC le, Robert, Archbishop of Rouen and Count of Évreux, possibly in reveng
3 CONC e for the support the Archbishop had provided to his brother against hi
3 CONC m. His uncle was exiled from Normandy, which resulted in the pope excom
3 CONC municating all of Normandy. The ex-communication was only lifted when t
3 CONC he Archbishop was allowed to return and restored as Count of Evreux. Ro
3 CONC bert's cousin Hugo III d'Ivry, Bishop of Bayeux, was also banished from N
3 CONC ormandy.
3 CONT
3 CONT Despite his domestic problems, Robert became involved in the civil war i
3 CONC n Flanders, fought between Baldwin V, Count of Flanders and his father B
3 CONC aldwin IV, whom the younger Baldwin had driven out of Flanders. Baldwin V
3 CONC , supported by his father-in-law, King Robert II of France, was persuad
3 CONC ed to make peace with his father in 1030.
3 CONT
3 CONT Robert took Herleva, daughter of Fulbert, a tanner of Falaise, as his m
3 CONC istress. A legend, still recounted by tour guides at Falaise, states th
3 CONC at Robert was on the walkway of his castle at Falaise looking down on t
3 CONC he river when he first sighted Herleva washing clothes with her skirts h
3 CONC itched high to keep them dry. The walkway on the roof still looks down o
3 CONC n the dyeing trenches cut into stone in the courtyard below. The exact d
3 CONC ate of their son William's birth is unknown but is believed to have tak
3 CONC en place sometime between September 1028 and September 1029. Herleva al
3 CONC so presented Robert with a daughter, Adelaide. Sometime after the birth o
3 CONC f William, Herleva's father Fulbert became chamberlain to Duke Robert. T
3 CONC he gap in their social standing rendered marriage to Herleva impossible
3 CONC , and she was eventually married to Herluin, Vicomte of Conteville. She w
3 CONC as to have three children with Herluin. Odo, later Bishop of Bayeux, wa
3 CONC s probably born c. 1030, Robert, Count of Mortain, 2nd Earl of Cornwall w
3 CONC as born circa 1031, a daughter Emma, was married to Richard LeGoz or Ri
3 CONC chard Goz, Viscount of Avranches.
3 CONT
3 CONT On the death of Robert II the Pious, king of France in 1031, Robert off
3 CONC ered shelter to his successor King Henry I of France against his mother
3 CONC , Queen Constance, who prefered the succession of her younger son Rober
3 CONC t, Duke of Burgundy, to the French throne. In return for his assistance
3 CONC , Henry I granted the French Vexin to Robert.
3 CONT
3 CONT In the early 1030s Duke Robert's cousin, Alan III, Duke of Brittany beg
3 CONC an expanding his influence from the area of Rennes and appeared to have d
3 CONC esigns on the area surrounding Mont Saint-Michel. Robert sacked Dol and s
3 CONC ucceeded in repelling Alan's attempts to raid Avranches and mounted a m
3 CONC ajor campaign against him. Alan appealed to their uncle, Archbishop Rob
3 CONC ert of Rouen, who at a meeting held at Mont-St-Michel negotiated peace b
3 CONC etween Robert and Alan III.
3 CONT
3 CONT Robert's English cousins, Edward and Alfred Atheling , the sons of his a
3 CONC unt Emma of Normandy and Ethelred the Redeless, King of England had bee
3 CONC n guests at the Norman Court since their exile from England by the Dani
3 CONC sh King Canute. Robert sent an embassy to England biding King Canute to "
3 CONC give them their own," the message having been met with disdain, he atte
3 CONC mpted to mount an invasion of England on their behalf but was prevented f
3 CONC rom doing so by unfavourable winds. The Gesta Normannorum Ducum claims t
3 CONC hat Canute dispatched envoys to Duke Robert offering to settle half the K
3 CONC ingdom of England on Edward and Alfred. After postponing the naval inva
3 CONC sion he chose to also leave deciding on the matter until after he retur
3 CONC ned from Jerusalem. The reinstatement of Robert Archbishop of Rouen saw a m
3 CONC arked change in Robert's attitude towards the Church. In an attempt at r
3 CONC econciliation, he restored property that he or his vassals had confisca
3 CONC ted from the church.
3 CONT
3 CONT After extracting an undertaking from his magnates to recognise his eigh
3 CONC t year old illegitimate son William his heir, Robert set out on pilgrim
3 CONC age to Jerusalem, an act of penitence. According to the Gesta Normannor
3 CONC um Ducum, he travelled by way of Constantinople to Jerusalem, where he f
3 CONC ell seriously ill and had to be carried in a litter, he died on the ret
3 CONC urn journey at Nicaea on 2 July 1035. Robert was succeeded by his son W
3 CONC illiam.
3 CONT
3 CONT William of Malmesbury recorded that decades later William sent a missio
3 CONC n to Constantinople and Nicaea, to bring his father's body back to Norm
3 CONC andy for burial. However, having travelled as far as Apulia in Italy on t
3 CONC he return journey, the envoys learned that William himself had meanwhil
3 CONC e died. They then decided to re-inter Robert's body in Italy.
