1 NOTE <b>Biography</b>
2 CONT Brocas came from a Gascon family whose fortunes were made through servi
2 CONC ce to the Kings of England, both in their native land and their new hom
2 CONC e, where they settled early in the 14th century. Bernard’s father, Sir J
2 CONC ohn Brocas, who was a member of the households of Edward II and Edward I
2 CONC II, held office under the latter as constable of Guildford castle and, i
2 CONC n fact if not in name, as master of the King’s horse, and made Windsor c
2 CONC astle the centre of his domestic and official life. His uncle, Master B
2 CONC ernard Brocas, an administrator of note, excelled as controller of Gasc
2 CONC ony and constable of Aquitaine.
2 CONT
2 CONT Bernard was a younger son, and of necessity set about making his own fo
2 CONC rtunes through military service. In 1346, aged about 16, he was ‘first a
2 CONC rmed on the seashore at Hogges’ (La Hogue) at the start of the invasion o
2 CONC f France which led to the battle of Crécy (in which his father and olde
2 CONC r brother, Oliver, also took part, both of them being ‘King’s knights’ )
2 CONC , and in the course of the next 40 years he also served in the wars of B
2 CONC rittany, Spain and Scotland. By late in 1354 he had been knighted and h
2 CONC ad won a place as a favoured member of the entourage of Henry of Grosmo
2 CONC nt, duke of Lancaster, an experienced and able military commander. In t
2 CONC hat year he travelled with Lancaster to Avignon (where the duke conduct
2 CONC ed negotiations with Innocent VI for peace beween England and France), a
2 CONC nd in January 1355 he successfully petitioned the Pope for indulgences f
2 CONC or visitors to a chapel in Windsor forest, and for an indult to choose h
2 CONC is own confessor. At the same time the duke requested a canonry for Bro
2 CONC cas’s uncle, Master Bernard, who subsequently, in July, named Lancaster a
2 CONC s a trustee of the estates at Beaurepaire and elsewhere, which he was p
2 CONC roposing to settle on his nephew and namesake. It was in July, too, tha
2 CONC t Brocas took out royal letters of protection to go on Lancaster’s prop
2 CONC osed expedition in aid of Charles of Navarre, and, although the plans w
2 CONC ere changed, in the following spring he was in Brittany with the duke, t
2 CONC he recently appointed lieutenant of the duchy, and he may have taken pa
2 CONC rt in the battle of Poitiers later that year. Before February 1358 Duke H
2 CONC enry granted him an annuity of £20 for life, from the issues of the hon
2 CONC our of Pontefract. Brocas was still in Lancaster’s employment the follo
2 CONC wing year, when he sailed to Normandy to arrest a man accused of embezz
2 CONC ling the revenues intended by the duke for fortifications, though he se
2 CONC ems to have left his service before Lancaster’s death in March 1361. Ce
2 CONC rtainly, before that date Brocas had commended himself to Edward III, w
2 CONC ho on 2 Aug. 1360 granted him an annuity of £40 at the Exchequer, and m
2 CONC ade him a knight of the royal chamber. Brocas again travelled to Norman
2 CONC dy in 1361, but whether for Lancaster or the King (or, indeed, to super
2 CONC vise his own affairs, which by this time involved dealings in large sum
2 CONC s of foreign currency) is unclear.
2 CONT
2 CONT In 1363 Brocas received an additional annuity of £10 from the Crown in r
2 CONC ecompense for his loss of the manor of Benham (Berkshire), which the Ki
2 CONC ng had by his gift; and in the same year, by Edward’s ‘special grace’, h
2 CONC e obtained a charter of free warren in his demesne lands in Hampshire. A
2 CONC s a ‘bachelor’ of Edward III Brocas was issued livery at the Household u
2 CONC ntil the end of the reign, and continued to serve his royal master both a
2 CONC t home and overseas. He may have fought at the battle of Najera in 1367
2 CONC ; three years later he recovered £60 due to him for wages for himself a
2 CONC nd his men ‘in the war’, and he was again overseas in 1372. He received m
2 CONC any other marks of patronage from the ageing monarch, notably a licence t
2 CONC o impark Beaurepaire, which entailed the enclosure of lands belonging t
2 CONC o the royal forest of Pamber, and, in 1373, the opportunity to exchange h
2 CONC is annuities for the wardenship for life of the manor of Compton Basset (
2 CONC Wiltshire). His proximity to the King is also suggested by his appearan
2 CONC ce as a witness to a conveyance of property to Edward’s mistress, Alice P
2 CONC errers. In 1376 Brocas was granted the keeping of Corfe castle and the w
2 CONC arren of Purbeck, but, although he went to the trouble of securing this p
2 CONC ost for life, he surrendered it in May 1377 in favour of John, Lord Aru
2 CONC ndel, receiving, presumably in exchange, the castle, town and manor of O
2 CONC diham at a farm of £55 a year.
2 CONT
2 CONT Brocas remained in favour at court under Richard II, and, indeed, was r
2 CONC eferred to as a ‘King’s knight’ for the rest of his life. Ten days afte
2 CONC r the beginning of the reign he was appointed captain of Calais, and se
2 CONC ems to have been often abroad until the spring of 1379. While at Calais h
2 CONC e was instructed to treat for the continuation of the alliance made bet
2 CONC ween Edward III and Louis, count of Flanders. He also took a prominent p
2 CONC art in the arrangements for the release of Waleran de Luxembourg, count o
2 CONC f St. Pol, a prisoner of war, which involved him not only in handling s
2 CONC ecurities for the count’s ransom of 100,000 francs but also in negotiat
2 CONC ions for his marriage to the King’s half-sister, Maud Holand, Lady Cour
2 CONC tenay. In 1384 Brocas was appointed keeper of Sangatte castle, the west
2 CONC ern outpost of Calais, though in the following year he joined the army w
2 CONC ith which Richard II attempted to invade Scotland. It is uncertain prec
2 CONC isely when he was appointed chamberlain to Richard’s queen, Anne of Boh
2 CONC emia, for the only evidence that he ever held this post is the inscript
2 CONC ion on his tomb; but it seems likely that he succeeded Sir Richard Adde
2 CONC rbury I* in this office in about 1387. The political conflicts of the r
2 CONC eign appear not to have troubled Brocas at all: he was commissioned to a
2 CONC dminister the oath of allegiance to the Appellants in March 1388, and e
2 CONC mployed on a committee to muster the troops of the earl of Arundel two m
2 CONC onths later; yet he remained close to Richard II: in 1391 as Richard’s a
2 CONC ttorney he took formal possession of property in Westminster, probably i
2 CONC n connexion with the rebuilding of Westminster hall, and on 17 Aug. 139
2 CONC 4 he was rewarded with an annuity of £40 for his good service to the la
2 CONC te queen.8 Brocas was well placed to obtain grants of lands in the temp
2 CONC orary possession of the Crown. Among those he received in the 1380s wer
2 CONC e the wardship of Robert Inkpen’s† lands in Hampshire, the joint keeper
2 CONC ship of the estates of the alien priory of Hayling (which he subsequent
2 CONC ly surrendered to John, Lord Montagu, the steward of the Household, in e
2 CONC xchange for custody of the lordship of Cranborne Chase during the minor
2 CONC ity of the earl of March), the joint keepership of the estates of Hambl
2 CONC e priory, rent-free, and the farm of the manor of Barford St. Martin, W
2 CONC iltshire. Finally, in June 1395, he secured for 200 marks a grant to hi
2 CONC mself and to Juliana, widow of his nephew Sir Edmund Missenden*, of cus
2 CONC tody of the Missenden estates (of which he was already a feoffee) durin
2 CONC g the minority of the heir, his great-nephew, Bernard.
2 CONT
2 CONT Brocas’s circle of acquaintance gathered around the Court; and his clos
2 CONC e associates included Sir Ivo Fitzwaryn*, the veteran campaigner Sir Ma
2 CONC tthew Gournay, and one of the royal clerks, Master John Chitterne. Undo
2 CONC ubtedly his most important connexion, and one which lasted for nearly a
2 CONC ll his life, was that formed with William of Wykeham, who served Edward I
2 CONC II successively as secretary, keeper of the privy seal, and chancellor. P
2 CONC robably his first meetings with Wykeham had taken place at Windsor cast
2 CONC le, for his father, like Wykeham, had been closely involved in the exte
2 CONC nsive building works there. Over the years Brocas witnessed a large num
2 CONC ber of deeds on his friend’s behalf; he was present when Wykeham was in
2 CONC stalled at Winchester in 1368; in 1377 Wykeham appointed him as chief s
2 CONC urveyor and keeper of the parks on the episcopal estates, and on anothe
2 CONC r occasion he excommunicated men who had poached in Brocas’s fish pond a
2 CONC t Beaurepaire. Clearly, their friendship was close, yet there is no evi
2 CONC dence that it ever led to Brocas’s participation in the bishop’s politi
2 CONC cal quarrels, of which the most serious was that of 1376 with John of G
2 CONC aunt. Indeed, Brocas himself seems to have been on amicable terms with G
2 CONC aunt; at least, in 1380 and again in 1382 the duke instructed the keepe
2 CONC r of his warren at Methwold (Norfolk) to allow him to hunt there when o
2 CONC n pilgrimage to Walsingham.
2 CONT
2 CONT During his years of service to Edward III and Richard II Brocas was bui
2 CONC lding up substantial landed estates. His uncle, Master Bernard Brocas, h
2 CONC ad purchased Beaurepaire in 1353 and not long afterwards settled it on h
2 CONC is nephew along with lands near Guildford in Surrey, including the mano
2 CONC rs of Peper Harrow and ‘Picard’s’ . Sir Bernard made Beaurepaire his se
2 CONC at and spent large sums on the house and park, obtaining royal licences t
2 CONC o enclose the latter in 1369 and to enlarge it in 1370 and 1388.11 Thro
2 CONC ugh his first marriage, to Agnes Vavasour, heiress of the junior branch o
2 CONC f the Vavasour family, he acquired Denton and five other manors in York
2 CONC shire, along with Weekley in Northamptonshire, but although they had is
2 CONC sue, a son named after his father, they were divorced before May 1360. A p
2 CONC eculiarity of the case was that the Church allowed both parties to marr
2 CONC y again, and Agnes then married Sir Henry Langfield. However, she lost p
2 CONC ossession of most of her estates, which were settled on the younger Ber
2 CONC nard, her son, and his wife.
2 CONT
2 CONT Sir Bernard’s own second marriage was even more advantageous than the f
2 CONC irst, for Mary Roches was collaterally descended from Peter des Roches, b
2 CONC ishop of Winchester. In 1361, on her mother’s death, she came into full p
2 CONC ossession of her patrimony, which included eight manors in Hampshire an
2 CONC d that of Bromley in Dorset. In addition, she brought Brocas a sizeable d
2 CONC ower from her former husband, Sir John Boarhunt: five manors and other s
2 CONC ubstantial properties in Hampshire. These last did not remain in Brocas
2 CONC ’s keeping for long, however, for in 1365 he and his wife endowed South
2 CONC wick priory with nearly all of the former Boarhunt lands, and in 1384, a
2 CONC fter her death, Brocas added the rest to the endowment. A more permanen
2 CONC t acquisition arising from this marriage was the post of master of the K
2 CONC ing’s buckhounds, an hereditary office attached in grand serjeanty to ‘
2 CONC Hunter’s Manor’ in Little Weldon (Northamptonshire), which Mary Brocas h
2 CONC eld as part of her jointure as Boarhunt’s wife. In 1366 Brocas came to a
2 CONC n agreement with the heir to the manor and office, Maud Lovell, by whic
2 CONC h he paid £100 in order to retain them for life and pass them on to his o
2 CONC wn descendants.
2 CONT
2 CONT When Sir Bernard’s father, Sir John, died in 1365, his heir was Sir Ber
2 CONC nard’s nephew, John, who himself died childless in 1377, leaving his un
2 CONC cle with an undisputed title to the manor of Broksham and lands at Heve
2 CONC r (Kent). Brocas was now also heir to his late father’s holdings in Ber
2 CONC kshire and Calais, but several years elapsed before he was able to obta
2 CONC in possession. Shortly before his death Sir John had given or sold his m
2 CONC anors of Clewer-Brocas and Didworth, along with property at New and Old W
2 CONC indsor and Bray, to Edward III, from whom he was to hold them, rent-fre
2 CONC e, for the rest of his life. Subsequently, the King had granted these p
2 CONC roperties to one of the masons working at Windsor castle, and it was no
2 CONC t until 1384 that Sir Bernard, with the assistance of Bishop Wykeham, f
2 CONC inally recovered them. He used part of this inheritance for the endowme
2 CONC nt of a chantry in Clewer church in his father’s memory. He was less su
2 CONC ccessful in the matter of his father’s property in Calais, which, alleg
2 CONC edly for default of keeping a watch, had escheated to the Crown and bee
2 CONC n commandeered by the King’s carpenters. Brocas brought a suit in Chanc
2 CONC ery to assert his rights, but it would appear that the issue was still u
2 CONC nresolved at his death, for the claims were renewed by his son. Sir Ber
2 CONC nard’s father had purchased the manor of Pollingfold in Ewhurst (Surrey
2 CONC ), and although this was initially settled on his stepmother, Isabel (w
2 CONC ho later married Sir Nicholas Lilling*), she relinquished her interest t
2 CONC o Sir Bernard in 1366. Thus, the extent of Brocas’s landed holdings flu
2 CONC ctuated over the course of his career, perhaps being at their most exte
2 CONC nsive in 1378, when he placed them in the hands of a group of feoffees, h
2 CONC eaded by Wykeham. He was then in possession of at least 13 manorial est
2 CONC ates in six different counties.
2 CONT
2 CONT To these he added the manors of Compton Chamberlain (Wiltshire) and Cla
2 CONC ybrook (Leicestershire), the inheritance of his third wife, Katherine, s
2 CONC ister of Elizabeth, Lady Clinton, and after the death of Sir Edward St. J
2 CONC ohn† in 1385, he also held for life the bailiwick of the forestership o
2 CONC f Woolmer and Alice Holt (Hampshire).15
2 CONT Brocas’s pilgrimages and religious foundations reveal him to have been a m
2 CONC an of conventional piety, wealthy enough to express his devoutness in s
2 CONC tyle. In 1375 he obtained a royal licence to grant lands worth £40 a ye
2 CONC ar to Titchfield abbey, for prayers for Edward III as well as for himse
2 CONC lf and his wife Mary. This endowment was never completed. Instead, Broc
2 CONC as founded a chantry at Southwick priory, his choice no doubt being inf
2 CONC luenced by his sister, Isabel Golafre, who had become a nun there after t
2 CONC he death of her second husband, and by Bishop Wykeham, himself a promin
2 CONC ent benefactor of the priory. Indeed, Wykeham presided in person at the c
2 CONC elebration of Brocas’s foundation. On a less impressive scale, Brocas a
2 CONC lso made a gift of property to Ivychurch priory (Wiltshire).
2 CONT
2 CONT Brocas died on 20 Sept. 1395. A mark of the esteem in which he had been h
2 CONC eld by Richard II was his burial, with great pomp and expense, in the c
2 CONC hapel of St. Edmund in Westminster abbey, close to the royal tombs. Bro
2 CONC cas’s widow took a vow of chastity before Bishop Stafford of Exeter, an
2 CONC d died three years later. His heir was another Sir Bernard Brocas, the o
2 CONC ffspring of his first marriage, who was to be executed in 1400 for plot
2 CONC ting to restore Richard II.17<b>Ref Volumes: 1386-1421Author: L. S. Woo
