1 BIRT
2 DATE 1324
2 PLAC Hampshire, England
1 EVEN Life
2 TYPE Misc
2 _SENT Sir Bernard Brocas, also Barnard Brocas Senior (1330–1395) was a promin
3 CONC ent commander in the English army during King Edward III's French campa
3 CONC igns of the Hundred Years War. He was also a close friend of the Black P
3 CONC rince and William of Wykeham.
3 CONT
3 CONT Brocas was the son of Sir John Brocas of Clewer in Berkshire, a Master o
3 CONC f the King's Horse. He grew up with the Black Prince at Windsor Castle, a
3 CONC t a time of rebuilding by the Royal architect William of Wykeham.[1] Af
3 CONC ter a scandalous first marriage,[1] to Agnes, daughter of Mauger Vavaso
3 CONC ur of Yorkshire, which ended in divorce, the Prince intended Brocas to m
3 CONC arry his cousin, Joan, the Fair Maid of Kent but when Joan said she lov
3 CONC ed Edward, he decided to marry her himself.[1] As compensation, he foun
3 CONC d Brocas another great heiress, Mary des Roches, a kinswoman of Peter d
3 CONC es Roches, Bishop of Winchester.
3 CONT
3 CONT Brocas fought with Edward at the Battles of Poitiers, Crécy and Nájera. A
3 CONC fter the Peace of Bretigny, he helped to settle Aquitaine and was appoi
3 CONC nted Constable there. It has been claimed that he captured and chopped o
3 CONC ff the head of a King of Morocco, but the story seems to be apocryphal.
3 CONT
3 CONT In England, Brocas acted as Queen's Chamberlain to Anne of Bohemia. He h
3 CONC ad residences at Clewer Brocas Manor in Berkshire,[1] and at Beaurepair
3 CONC e in Sherborne St John and Roche Court near Fareham, both in Hampshire. H
3 CONC e was a great patron of Southwick Priory. He served as High Sheriff of W
3 CONC iltshire for 1382 and married Katharine, widow of Hugh Tyrell. Brocas w
3 CONC as MP for Wiltshire in 1391 and then MP eight times for Hampshire.
3 CONT
3 CONT He married three times and had at least five children,[1] amongst them, S
3 CONC ir Bernard Brocas the Younger, who was executed for treason in 1400.
3 CONT
3 CONT Brocas died on 20 September 1395 and was buried in St Edmund's Chapel i
3 CONC n Westminster Abbey, where his fine effigial monument can still be seen t
3 CONC oday.
3 CONT
3 CONT The name Brocas lives on in the name Viscount Brocas, one of the subsid
3 CONC iary titles of the Earl Jellicoe.
