0 _PLAC Austrasia
1 NOTE <b>Austrasia</b> was a territory which formed the north-eastern section o
2 CONC f the Kingdom of the Franks from the 6th to 8th centuries, ruled by the F
2 CONC rankish Merovingian and Carolingian dynasties during the Early Middle A
2 CONC ges. It was centred on the Meuse, Middle Rhine, and the Moselle rivers, a
2 CONC nd was the original territory of the Franks, including both the so-call
2 CONC ed Salians and Rhineland Franks, which Clovis I, King of the Franks (48
2 CONC 1–511) conquered after first taking control of the bordering part of Ro
2 CONC man Gaul (present-day northwestern France), which is sometimes describe
2 CONC d in this period as Neustria.
2 CONT In 561, Austrasia became a separate kingdom within the Frankish kingdom a
2 CONC nd was ruled by the Merovingian king Sigebert I (561–575). In the 7th a
2 CONC nd 8th centuries, it was the powerbase from which the Carolingians, ori
2 CONC ginally mayors of the palace of Austrasia, took over the rule of all Fr
2 CONC anks, all of Gaul, most of Germany, and northern Italy. After this peri
2 CONC od of unification, the now larger Frankish Empire was once again divide
2 CONC d between eastern, central, and western sub-kingdoms (West Francia, Mid
2 CONC dle Francia, and East Francia), with the new version of the eastern kin
2 CONC gdom eventually becoming the foundation of the Kingdom of Germany.
2 CONT <b><u>Geography</u></b>
2 CONT Austrasia was centered on the Middle Rhine, including the basins of the M
2 CONC oselle, Main, and Meuse rivers. It bordered on Frisia and Saxony to the n
2 CONC orth, Thuringia to the east, Swabia and Burgundy to the south and to Ne
2 CONC ustria to the southwest. The exact boundary between Merovingian Neustri
2 CONC a and Austrasia is unclear with respect to areas such as the medieval c
2 CONC ounties of Flanders, Brabant and Hainaut, and areas immediately to the s
2 CONC outh of these.
2 CONT Metz served as the Austrasian capital, although some Austrasian kings r
2 CONC uled from Reims, Trier and Cologne. Other important cities included Ver
2 CONC dun, Worms and Speyer. Fulda monastery was founded in eastern Austrasia i
2 CONC n the final decade of the Merovingian period.
2 CONT In the High Middle Ages, its territory became divided among the duchies o
2 CONC f Lotharingia and Franconia in Germany, with some western portions incl
2 CONC uding Reims and Rethel passing to France.
2 CONT Its exact boundaries were somewhat fluid over the history of the Franki
2 CONC sh sub-kingdoms, but Austrasia can be taken to correspond roughly to th
2 CONC e territory of present-day Luxembourg, parts of eastern Belgium, north-
2 CONC eastern France (Lorraine and Champagne-Ardenne), west-central Germany (
2 CONC the Rhineland, Hesse and Franconia) and the southern Netherlands (Limbu
2 CONC rg, North Brabant, with a salient north of the Rhine including Utrecht a
2 CONC nd parts of Gelderland).
2 CONT <b><u>History</u></b>
2 CONT After the death of the Frankish king Clovis I in 511, his four sons par
2 CONC titioned his kingdom amongst themselves, with Theuderic I receiving the l
2 CONC ands that were to become Austrasia. Descended from Theuderic, a line of k
2 CONC ings ruled Austrasia until 555, when it was united with the other Frank
2 CONC ish kingdoms of Chlothar I, who inherited all the Frankish realms by 55
2 CONC 8. He redivided the Frankish territory amongst his four sons, but the f
2 CONC our kingdoms coalesced into three on the death of Charibert I in 567: A
2 CONC ustrasia under Sigebert I, Neustria under Chilperic I, and Burgundy und
2 CONC er Guntram. These three kingdoms defined the political division of Fran
2 CONC cia until the rise of the Carolingians and even thereafter.
2 CONT From 567 to the death of Sigebert II in 613, Neustria and Austrasia fou
2 CONC ght each other almost constantly, with Burgundy playing the peacemaker b
2 CONC etween them. These struggles reached their climax in the wars between B
2 CONC runhilda and Fredegund, queens respectively of Austrasia and Neustria. F
2 CONC inally, in 613, a rebellion by the nobility against Brunhilda saw her b
2 CONC etrayed and handed over to her nephew and foe in Neustria, Chlothar II. C
2 CONC hlothar then took control of the other two kingdoms and set up a united F
2 CONC rankish kingdom with its capital in Paris. During this period the first <
2 CONC i>majores domus</i> or mayors of the palace appeared. These officials a
2 CONC cted as mediators between the king and the people in each realm. The fi
2 CONC rst Austrasian mayors came from the Pippinid family, which experienced a s
2 CONC low but steady ascent until it eventually displaced the Merovingians on t
2 CONC he throne.
2 CONT In 623, the Austrasians asked Chlothar II for a king of their own and h
2 CONC e appointed his son Dagobert I to rule over them with Pepin of Landen a
2 CONC s regent. Dagobert's government in Austrasia was widely admired. In 629
2 CONC , he inherited Neustria and Burgundy. Austrasia was again neglected unt
2 CONC il, in 633, the people demanded the king's son as their own king again. D
2 CONC agobert complied and sent his elder son Sigebert III to Austrasia. Hist
2 CONC orians often categorise Sigebert as the first <i>roi fainéant</i>, or d
2 CONC o-nothing king, of the Merovingian dynasty. His court was dominated by t
2 CONC he mayors. In 657, the mayor Grimoald the Elder succeeded in putting hi
2 CONC s son Childebert the Adopted on the throne, where he remained until 662
2 CONC . Thereafter, Austrasia was predominantly the kingdom of the Arnulfing m
2 CONC ayors of the palace and their base of power. With the Battle of Tertry i
2 CONC n 687, Pepin of Heristal defeated the Neustrian king Theuderic III and e
2 CONC stablished his mayoralty over all the Frankish kingdoms. This was even r
2 CONC egarded by contemporaries as the beginning of his "reign". It also sign
2 CONC alled the dominance of Austrasia over Neustria, which would last until t
2 CONC he end of the Merovingian era.
2 CONT In 718, Charles Martel had Austrasian support in his war against Neustr
2 CONC ia for control of all the Francian realms. He was not king himself, but a
2 CONC ppointed Chlothar IV to rule in Austrasia. In 719, Francia was united b
2 CONC y Martel's family, the Carolingian dynasty, under Austrasian hegemony. W
2 CONC hile the Frankish kings continued to divide up the Frankish realm in di
2 CONC fferent ways over subsequent generations, the term Austrasia was only u
2 CONC sed occasionally after the Carolingian dynasty.
